Very heavy rain

2.5 cm at Moonbi
2 cm hail at Wandsworth damaged a colourbond roof
57 kt  gust at Braidwood. Radar echoes up to 30 DBZ in area.
Dry microburst. 72 kt gust at Bathurst.
Dry microburst at Mt Boyce with gust to 58 kts.
2.5 cm hail at Ballina. Some cloud rotation noted.

2.2 cm hail 5 km NW of Bowraville
VHR 5 km NW of Bowraville

TV/CB antenennae blown down
2 cm hail.
Damaged property, especially the local RSL club where most skylights were damaged.
HOUSE SHAKING, TREES BENT OVER TO GROUND AT ELDEE.
Limbs screwed off trees, express train sound.
2 cm hail. No damage reported.
Wet microbursts which produced roof and tree damage.
60 kt wind gust.
Large trees blown down, some fell on cars. At least 3 homes unroofed and damage to many others.
VERY HEAVY RAIN 10 KM SW OF ORANGE
55 kt winds at Oberon. No damage reported.

Wind gusts ranged from 50 kt at Box Hill, 56 at Penrith, 48 at Sydney Airport, 65 at Barrenjoey Headland to 72 at Fort Denison and 80 knots at Riverview Observatory.  Widespread damage which included roofs, windows, trees, cars (2 cars overturned at Mona Vale) and powerlines.
RAIN CAUSED STREET GUTTERS TO OVERFLOW

VERY NARROW AND TALL, FAIRLY STRAIGHT FROM GROUND TO CLOUD LEVEL. OBSERVED HALFWAY BETWEEN MACQUARIE CENTRE AND BLUE MTS.  NO DAMAGE OBSERVED. ON SYDNEY HARBOUR AROUND SAME TIME TWO WATERSPOUTS WERE OBSERVED NEAT ROSE BAY.
3 cm hail at Newport.
EXTENSIVE DAMAGE TO PROPERTY.  ONE MAN TAKEN TO HOSPITAL SUFFERING SUSPECTED SPINAL INJURIES AFTER BEING TRAPPED INSIDE A COLLAPSED SHED.
More than 60 homes damaged, mostly roof and windows.  Trees and powerlines down.  Bit like a bomb going off.
6 .3 CM HAIL AT FORBES.
WINDS DAMAGED ROOFS, WALLS, TILES. TREES BLOWN DOWN, CARS DAMAGED. FENCES BLOWN DOWN AND POWERLINES DOWN.
HAIL DAMAGED CAR
STORM TRAVELLED TOWARD NE. NO DAMAGE REPORTED.
NO DAMAGE REPORTED.
HAIL CAUSED SOME DAMAGE TO CARS, GARDENS AND WINDOWS.
WIND SNAPPED LARGE TREES AND KILLED A COW
DAMS FILLED, SOME MINOR WATER DAMAGE
NO DAMAGE REPORTED.
68 KT GUST. NO DAMAGE REPORTED.
6 large transmission towers failed..
WATER BURST DAM, STOCK LOSSES, FENCES DAMAGED. WATER DAMAGE OCCURRED IN SOME LOCAL SHOPS. SOME UNCONFIRMED REPORTS OF 115 MM IN 45 MINS HAVE RESULTED.
No reported damage.
Wind and rain damage estimated at over 1 million dolars. roofs lifted, numerous shops flooded, widespread tree damage. Microburst was seen before arrival. Hail reported in the vicinity.

Possibility of tornado but not confirmed more likely a severe downburst. No observation of any funnel cloud. However, damage in strips about 1km wide. Tops of some poplar trees observed to be twisted off.
Some hail had jagged edges and reported to be elongated like flat stones or eggs by a number of spotters.
Backyards and houses in Armidale area flooded.

Winds up to 100km/hr. No exact figure. AWS lost power during storm. Fibro and brick home ripped apart. Small Tamair aeroplane destoyed. 32 tonne Neptune aircraft swung around 90 degreees. Some houses in a new estate badly damaged by wind and rain. Roofing iron blown off hangars. 6 mm plate galss window at airport blown in. SOme injuries due to flying glass.
Heavy rain caused minor flash floods and erosion to roads
Winds uprooted trees and snapped branches.
No reported damage from heavy rain.
Branches broken off trees.
About 100 trees damaged or blown within 1km radius of Invergowrie (west of Armidale). Two houses damaged, several sheds destroyed.

Most hail was olnly about 2 cm but some jagged and up to 5 cm. Also hail formed layers in some parts up to a depth of 7cm of small hail. Hail shattered glass windows and put holes in thin iron roofs. Other types of roofing was damaged also. Hail mainly on the north side of Uralla.
Rain caused flash flooding which rose the level of the river through town 2.5 m over the level of the bridge.
Nearly all rooves blown off buildings on one local farm.
Local flash flooding. Power blackouts between Forbes and Condoblin
Hail reported to be the size of hen eggs. Damage to crops and trees. Storm made distinctive track of damage 2 km wide.
No reported damage.
Paroo River rose by 17cm
No reported damage.
No reported damage.
No reported damage
Houses and sheds damaged nearTamworth airport. Trees brought down by wind.
Some trees and large branches fallen.
Wind measured as 102 km/hr (55 knots) "unofficially" Gust strength entered from AWS at 1427EDST
No reported damage
Winds at Green Point and Niagara Park estimated at 80-90 km/hr. Estimation from damage caused. Damage, however, not reported.
Hail reported also at Regents Park as 2.3cm

Flash floods occurred. Numerous streets in Sydney covered with water. Pacific Hwy at Killara blocked and Military Rd Cremorne closed. Pacific Hwy Killara flooded.Newbridge Rd Moorebank closed, Cumberland Hwy Wentworthville closed due to flooding.
Trees stripped of leaves and shrubs broken.

Farm sheds and and trees blown onto houses. Farm equipment blown away or destroyed; an almost full water tank blown away. A piggery was virtually demolished and power lines were blown down. Hail shower was reported as heavy but small (,2 cm) and brief.
No reported damage. Isolated case.
No reported damage. Checked by interrogating rain gauge in the area.
Wagga, Uranquinty, Ladysmith and surrounds all had shops, house and roads flooded.

Roof gutters and street drains overflowing in Chisholm (Canberra suburb). Top soil washed from gardens onto the street. Woden Creek flooded 1 to 1.5 m above the road level. This is in the Wanniassia Hills area. Many other roads closed around Canberra. The storm cells were reported to be moving north to south along the Brindabell Ranges.
Peter Grimmond reported event. A detailed report with photos has been sent to Sydney Regional Office. Hail strewn across a field. Amazingly no reported injuries.
No damage reported.

Trees blown over, roofs were lifted at Ourimbah and Lisarow. The towns of Narara, Wyoming and Matcham were also hit. No injuries or deaths but some luck escapes. A poplar tree was blown over and smashed a caravan and another treee fell and smashed school classroom at Ourimbah
Hail siz of golf balls damaged the roof of the Bowling Club. A spotter from the P.O. reported 2 cm size hailstones and 22 mm rain in 60 minutes
Fort Denison recorded wind gusting to 61 knots. No reported damage. Evening sond trace recognizable as probable wet microburts
Spotter phoned report in. No damage.
No damage reported.
Hail the size of "fair sized marbles" reorted by Daily Advertiser (Wagga). Sorghum and millet crops flattened by rain and hail.
Trees blown down and fences damaged by blown branches. Crops damaged by heavy rain and hail.
Golf ball sized hail. Some damage to car bodies.
18.6 MM IN 10 MINS AND 41.0 MM IN 60 MINS AT RICHMOND AWS
VERY HEAVY RAIN CAUSED SOME SHOP FLOODING IN CBD.
5 CM AT RYDE, 2  AT DENISTONE/MANLY/ROSEVILLE/HARBORD, 3 AT PYMBLE, BELROSE, FRENCH'S FOREST, 2.5 AT NARABEEN BEACH, 4 AT LANE COVE NATIONAL PARK/GORDON.
DAMAGE TO HOMES, CARS AND CROPS.
Hail fell out of brown/green cloud at Brushgrove. Seemed heavier over Maclean.

Information passed on from Mike Bergen who spoke to the man who witnessed the funnel cloud while travelling on a bus to Wagga. The cell was about 15-20 km south of the coach. The cell was large, solitary and funnel cloud was distinct. The tornado was not observed to have touched-down"."
CARS, WINDOWS, ROOFS AND OTHER PROPERTY DAMAGE REPORTED.

O'Brien calls it a 'willy willy'. Steve Malley from Canberra Met Office obseved the tornado also. O'Brien writes "a band of uintense but brief rain and wind squalls crossed the region...at about 2145 [LT] rain and strong gusty E to SE developed to 60 km/hr. By 2000 [LT] the wind veered rapidly through 180 degrees with equally strong W/NW winds."
A person was struck by lightning with burns to chest.
Hail damaged sugar cane crops, near Maclean
HAIL DAMAGED CARS, WINDOWS, CROPS AND PROPERTY. SWATH 1 KM WIDE x 3 KMS LONG.
57 kt gust with a line of TS.
Event occurred in southern part of township.
Some trees were brought down.  Other minor damage reported.
No damage reported.
Flash flooding reported
No damage reported.
No damage reported
Extensive fencing damage with rain filling all dams.
No damage reported.
No damage reported.
Some tree damage reported.
Very heavy rain at Geneva near Kyogle
No damage reported.
Some crop damage.
Some car and crop damage.
Some crop damage.
Two homes unroofed and trees were blown down.
No damage reported. Conglomerate form.
No damage reported.
Cars, trees and roofs damaged.  A horse was killed.
A 6.6 cm stone weighed 43.5g.  Limbs stripped off trees, cars damaged, roof tiles broken.
Hail damaged cars as well as other property.  Some other western suburbs reported stones between 2 and 3.5 cm.
Wet microburst damaged a number of homes in an area bounded by Pittwater Rd/Taminga St/Corniche Rd and Jendi Ave.  Trees down, powerlines down, roofs and cars damaged.
Wet microburst damaged an area along Prince Alfred Pde and Bardo Rd.  Trees down, powerlines down,  roofs and cars damaged.
2 HOUSES UNROOFED, TREES UPROOTED AND DAMAGE TO GARDENS.
Trees blown down over about 3 acres.
20 homes damaged, 4 severely, one total write off. No casulities reported.
No damage reported.
No damage reported.
No damage was reported.
No damage reported.
Gust occurred at Homebush Bay AWS.
No damage reported.
No damage reported.
WIND DAMAGE TO HOMES WITH 2 ROOFS OFF AND EXTENSIVE DAMAGE TO OTHERS.  LARGE TREES BLOWN DOWN.
TREES DOWN AND SATELLITE RECEIVING DISH BLOWN FROM ROOF AT UNE.
GUST REPORTED FROM AWS. Trees down and some homes damaged.
5 houses damaged as well as the TAFE college and hospital.
Houses damaged.
Houses damaged.
Wind damaged property, including homes, cars and powerlines, mostly from fallen trees. Winmalee and other parts of the central and higher mountains were affected.
Wind damage due to trees being uprooted and falling on homes, cars and powerlines in the Campbelltown, Penrith and Oakhurst areas.
Wind damage to homes and powerlines due to fallen trees.
VHR and FF occurred in a number of ACT suburbs including Gilmore, Holder, Fadden, Gowrie, Bonython, Gordon and Kambah West.
Trees down and crops damaged.
Flash flooding in and around the township.  Parts of the Newell Highway closed.
Hail lasted 5 mins.
Damage spread over 20 farms. Entire crops damaged. Trees and fences blown down.
Entire crops damaged over 20 farms
ROOFS OFF HOMES, ONE HOME DESTROYED.  POWERLINES AND TREES DOWN.
Roofs off homes, powerlines down, trees uprooted and crops flattened.
Property damage including cars.
Flattened crops and damaged property including cars.
TRACTORS TURNED UPSIDE DOWN, ROOFS OFF SHEDS AND HOMES.
2 ft diameter trees snapped by wind.
LARGE LIMBS BLOWN OFF TREES AND TREES UPROOTED.
No damage reported.
Trees down, roofs blown off homes, powerlines down and windows broken.
Hail smashed plastic buckets.
Snapped trees and blew roofs off homes.
Trees uprooted and destroyed crops.
Hail smashed windows, killed animals and totally desroyed crops.
Damage to cars.
Trees down and roofs damaged.
Wind pulled out trees and damaged roofs.
3 roofs off in Lismore and large trees blown down.
Trees uprooted and roofs taken off homes.
Damage to fruit trees.
Snapped 0.5 m dia tree with debris flying everywhere.
Car stuck in flooded creek crossing.
Hail damaged car, broke house windows and stripped trees.
Roads washed away and a car was submerged for a short period of time.

Wind gusts in excess of 48 kt at Schofields (est) with trees blown down and some uprooted. A sighting of a funnel cloud taking out tops of trees was reported from the St Leonards area at around 0815 UTC.
Trees down, roofs off homes and the local pub.
CREEKS FLOODED AND EXTENSIVE ROAD DAMAGE.
ROAD DAMAGE.
25 people evacuated from the town. Flash flooding occurred in surrounding areas.
Small amounts of damage to trees and plants.
Roofs off some buildings and trees down.
Flooding of sheds and paddocks. River banks damaged.
Trees blown down and some other minor property damage.
Extensive roof and property damage in MM as well as Peats Ridge. A 45 m solid metal shed was uprooted at Peats Ridge.
Damage (tree & house) along the Pacific H'Way. Wind damage reported from Gosford and Wyong areas.
Trees blown down, roof blown off high school.
Hail reported from Ourimbah, Kariong, Gosford, Wyong and Tuggerah.
3 cm at Faulconbridge which damaged a car and stripped trees.
A verbal report of 8 cm from nearby.
100 homes blown off stumps and roofs blown off. 1 boy seriously injured. At 0857 AWS came back on air with a report of gust to 97 kt, this is very suspect!.
54 kt gust from 280 at 0743.
Roofing iron torn off home and trees uprooted.
Rain gauge blew over.
Roof blown off woolshed.
Trees snapped and other minor damage occurred.
TREES BLOWN DOWN. SWATHE 1 KM LONG AND 100 M WIDE.
Trees limbs blown off and shallow rooted trees blown over.
Damage to roof.
TREES DOWN AND ROOFS PARTIALLY DAMAGED.
2 TO 9 CM HAIL IN THE GRAFTON AREA (9CM AT RAMORNIE) DAMAGE TO ROOFS, TREES AND CARS.
Rain washed away a large amount of fencing.
Local flooding through some homes and sheds.
WATER DAMAGE TO ROADS.
Large tree fell on house, many trees blown down.
Water in home and sheds.
SOLAR PANELS BLOWN OFF ROOF OF RESIDENCE.
TREES DOWN.
Tree snapped, large trees uprooted (1m dia). Sheds and fences damaged or destroyed. Horse killed by flying debris.
Flash flooding along Lane Cove Rd.
Soil erosion and road flooding.
Cars dented.
Localised flash flooding with erosion of gravel drives and nature strips.
Extensive crop and property damage throughout the Wagga area.
Trees blown down, some property damage.
Roads blocked and creeks flooded.
SOME STRIPPING OF FOLIAGE.
No damage reported.
Trees and shrubs stripped and windows broken.

400 to 500 kg tree completely stripped and thrown 150 m. Sheds completely demolished, cars and a bus pushed off the road, the bus was rolled over. A sheep was thrown 1 km. Wild-life killed. A 2 ton cattle feeder was thrown 300 yards uphill.  The funnel cloud was black in colour.
A gust to 50 kt about 2 mins before from 240 deg.
Dams filled very quickly, some flash flooding occurred.
Large trees uprooted.
Hail lasted 3 min.
Flash flooding caused some roads to be cut.

Ironbark trees 600mm dia broken and pulled out of ground, destroyed a house and several sheds. Extensive damage to fences, moved a 4 tonne truck several lengths. Loud roaring noise heard as well as a deep humming sound.
Tin roofs dented, tiles broken.
Hailstones went straight thru' BBQ cover.
See hail entry.

400 homes and buildings damaged, insurance bill around $70m, car damage around $30 mil. Roofs most common claim, followed by windows, awnings, outdoor glass structures, pergolas and patios and garden furniture.
Lambs with backs broken, roof, window and tree damage.
Woolshed and other buildings damaged. Trees felled.
Some structural damage occurred. Steel awnings blown down.
One house reported window damage.
Water broke banks of river and caused problems in streets
Some damage to property (cars, homes and aircraft)
Windows broken, gardens destroyed and cars damaged.
Water flowed through house. No rain was reported in Manilla itself.
12 houses damaged, 100 windows damaged and many trees blown over. Two minor injuries were reported from a caravan that was damaged.
Gust severely damaged local council building.
20 houses and the local police station unroofed and local communications tower blown down.
Many homes, shops and factories unroofed with fallen trees blocking major roads, bringing down powerlines and crushing some cars.
Many trees uprooted and some property damage.
Gust cut a 200 m swathe through the town, pushing over a 5 tonne truck and damaged more than 30 homes.
Trees blown down over road, one fell across a car that had pulled off the road killing the driver.
Some roof damage reported.
Trees blown down, some roof damage. Anemometer blown off mast.
Some damage to cereal crops.
Damage to cereal crops.
Leaves stripped off trees and shrubs.
Some water damage reported.

A combination of VHR and a high tide resulted in local flooding which reached a depth of 1.5 metres and flooded most businesses in the Coffs CBD. 300 people were evacuated, one woman was drowned. The extent of damage caused the State government to declare the area a disaster. Other 24 hr falls reported in the area were Bowra Sugarloaf 405 mm, Girralong 257, Bellbrook 202, Dorrigo 146, Smokey Cape 135, Mount Seaview 127 and Wauchope 119.
55 kt at 0639 from 280 deg and 60 kt at 0638 from 270 deg.
Several houses unroofed and trees broken.
Some trees uprooted. Some damage reported from Ulamambri and Coonabarabran around same time.
Several houses unroofed as well as the local bowling club.
Flash flooding washed livestock out to sea. Severe soil erosion.
DAMAGE TO CARS.
Flash flooding made some roads impassable.
Roof and car damage.
About 40 homes sustained damage along with many cars and factories. One man died when his car swerved off the road and hit a tree. Six people were injured mostly from flying glass.
Trees uprooted and some roofs off homes.
Some damage to house and garden.
Airport hangar doors blown out, Ses building lost its roof, some other minor damage reported.
Damage confined to 600m wide belt. Two huge trees uprooted and trunks shattered.
Trees uprooted and sheds unroofed.
Trees up to 800 mm dia broken off and blown over
Sheets of water, dams overflowing.
Damage to vineyards around $300,000.
Hail ripped tent and shredded branches from trees.
Some tree and roof damage reported. Damage also reported from  Leeton, Hay and Narrandera again in the form of tree and roof damage.
No damage reported.
2 chimmneys blown down, steel roof on church blown off, a few homes lost their roofs and a tree was blown down onto a car.
Roofs off buildings, caravans pushed over and trees blown down. Five transmission towers failed 6km north of Bungendore.
King Georges Rd at Kogarah flooded.
Severely damaged roofing and cars and destroyed crops.
Trees blown down and buildings damaged.
Eatonsville, South Grafton, Grafton and Copmanhurst were all affected with a lot of damage to buildings, trees, cars and crops. 4 cm hail was a fairly common size.
Very heavy metal hay trailer lifted off ground and carried at least 200 m. Some property damage, such as roofs off, occurred.
Many roofs off homes, sugar cane flattened, powerlines and trees down and caravans overturned.
Numerous areas around Grafton affected with Junction Hill being the worst hit with at least 100 homes damaged. All up 150 homes have been damaged, and sugar cane crops flattened.
Some minor damage to caravans and plants.
Braches ripped off trees. 6 houses damaged, trees down and roofs off at Taren Point.
Homes damaged and powerlines down. 50 odd jobs SES.
Windows broken, cars damaged.
Roofs off, homes damaged, powerlines and trees blown down.
Windows broken, cars damaged.
Some big trees blown down over road.
Some roof damage reported.
Roof damage and trees down. Other areas affected were Narrabeen/Newport/Mona Vale/Hornsby.
Damage to cars, buildings and other property at both Newport and Mona Vale. Hail was also reported from surrounding suburbs around 2 to 3cm. Bilgola Plateau reorted 3cm.
Flash flooding reported from Pennant Hills area as well at 0400 UTC.
Some branches blown down.
Hail was jagged and multi-layered.
Lots of trees blown down around the town. 1000 hectare of cotton destoyed nearby.
Large limbs off trees, some snapped off at base. Some structural damage to sheds.
Trees down and aerials bent.
Some roofs peeled off sheds. Damage also reported from Cessnock.
Damage reported from Lake Macquarie City, Newcastle, Port Stephens, Cooranbong, Cessnock, Muswellbrook and Singleton. One person drowned on Lake Macquarie.
Big gum trees snapped.
Powerlines down and some roofs lifted. Cars damaged.
Powerlines and trees down, roofs lifted.
Severe damage to cotton crops.
Streams of mud through Lithgow upto 1 metre in depth.
Local flooding.
Local creeks overflowed.
4 homes destroyed, 18 houses unroofed and 77 homes sustained significant damage. Schools, businesses and public buildings severely damaged.
Some homes flooded by 600 - 900 mm of water.
ROOFS BLOWN OFF HOUSES AND TREES TWISTED.
Roof and window damage in the Canowindra, Orange, Cargo areas. A silo was blown off its foundations at Cargo.
STRATHFIELD SHOPPING CENTRE FLOODED.
Flash flooding reported from Hoxton Park as well as the CBD where Grace Bros store had 3 floors flooded.
Powerlines down and some roofs partly torn off.
Six houses unroofed.
Some houses unroofed.
Cars damaged by falling trees.
Damage to cars.
Damage to golf course, beach and caravans through flash flooding.
Damage to houses, large trees uprooted and two haysheds flattened.
House and property damage in the area. Similar at Eumungerie at around same time.
Hail smashed windows on houses and cars and stripped trees. Similar damage and hail size at Eumungerie at around same time.
Flash flooding across the Dunedoo Rd.
Large trees uprooted and some roof damage in the village.
One death occurred when a tree branch fell on a baby. Damage reported in the Darlington Point/Griffith/Leeton areas.
Over 200 tasks performed by the SES mostly for property damage, trees down over roads,etc.
A few housed unroofed and trees uprooted.
Some roads and houses flooded.
Some gutters and roads awash.
Large trees brought down, large branches broken.
Leaves stripped by hail.

Worst areas affected were Greystanes, Blacktown, Parramatta, Holroyd, Greenacre and Canterbury where 420 jobs were attended to by the SES. Most damage resulted from trees and branches falling into houses and across roads, a few homes were unroofed. The Pacific Highway was closed due to fallen trees in the Greenacre area.
Many large trees uprooted, 2 sheds and unoccupied farm cottage partially unroofed.
Powerlines down, trees across roads disrupting traffic for about an hour. Somes roofs off. Some rotation evident in cloudbase. Some homes also unroofed at nearby Urunga.
Trees down, powerlines down blocking one street for a time.
Gutters overflowed and 2 offices were flooded.
Roads flooded in the area.
Large trees blown down and some damage to gardens.
Some roof damage and trees down.
Damage to garden.
Some flash flooding occurred.
Trees and limbs down. Shed blown 100 m off machinery shed.
Roads washed away and cut by flood waters.
Some fruit trees damaged.
Large branched ripped off trees, medium size trees uprooted. A number of roads blocked due fallen trees.
Local flooding of laundry.
A few houses damaged, half a roof off one.
Fallen trees closed north and south bound lanes of Pacific Highway between Gosford and Kariong.

Extensive flash flooding occurred overa wide area. A lot of water was lying on roads around western, eastern Sydney and especially along the northern beaches. The rainfall rate quoted is an average for over the general area.
Very heavy rain and flash flooding reported from a wide area of the Sydney metro area.
Very localised flash flooding in Port Macquarie.
Some damage to trees and houses.
Significant number of trees blown down. Some damage to homes and other property.
Dented iron roof so much that it had to be replaced.
Some damage reported mostly to small plants.
39 caravans overturned or damaged at local caravan park (6 destroyed), 26 units damaged in retirement village, 11 homes suffered roof damage.
One large 4wd rolled over another car ended up ontop of another. A weatherboard house was severely damaged. A baby was sucked out of the house but fortunately was uninjured.

All major road and train lines to Wollongong cut due to rain with numerous mud-slides also occurring. A person drowned when trying to drive across a flooded creek at Bellambi. 50 plus homes were flooded and some homes were dislodged from their foundations.24 hour rain totals were 341.5 at Keiraville, 316.5 at Figtree (111 mm in 180 min) and 316 at Wollongong.
Trees stripped and blown down.
Roofs gutters overflowing.
Hail caused some roofs to collapse.
Many trees uprooted and two sheds lost roofs.
Tree branches blown down.
Narrow swathe of 1 km around Mungo Brush.
Large branches down and structural damage to buildings.
Large branches down.
Hail smashed through water tank and damaged crops. 4 cm was most common size.
New England Highway closed for a period of time due to hail on road.
Damage reported.
Localised flooding on western outskirts of Tamworth.
Flash flooding reported in some creeks.
Clouds green in colour
Large cedar tree uprooted
Very heavy rain in the Hills area of Sydney. Cars underwater in the Winston Hills area.
Light plane blown 100m after breaking mooring. Many trees uprooted and powerlines down.
Some local flooding reported in the Tatten area.
Some local flash flooding reported.
55 kt at 0756 UTC.
Gutters overflowed and 10cm of water over the road.
Trees blown down.
Large trees blown down.
Garden shredded and oat crop blown down.
At least 6 homes were unroofed and many others damaged. Damage to other property was reported.
3 houses unroofed, 100 others sustained roof damage. A light aircraft was destroyed and 3 others were damaged.

Spotter report (James Harris) of an intense hail storm near Bilpin. Roads are impassable with large amounts of 1-2cm sized hailstones, but the largest stones that fell were in the 2-3cm range.

Spotter report of damaging wind gusts from a thunderstorm just south of the Oaks. Reported many sizeable tree branches down, and that one hit his car while he was making the report. No estimate of gust strength given. Heavy rain but no hail and no mention of flash flooding.
35mm recorded in 30 minutes on a hydrology gauge from a thunderstorm at Oakdale. This amount exceeds flash flood criteria.

Spotter report (Michael Mostyn) of a hailstorm, most common size 2cm, with the largest up to 3cm in diameter. Hail fell for 50 minutes, with vegetation damage, power failures and mobile phone outages all impacts from the storm. This report also included flash flooding.
Spotter report (Michael Mostyn) of very heavy rainfall and some flash flooding from a storm at Kanahooka. No figures given for rainfall. This report also included large hail.

44mm recorded at Cringila in 30 minutes on a hydrology gauge from a thunderstorm, including a period of 30mm in 15 minutes. This exceeds flash flood thresholds, and is approximately a 1 in 20 year event.
Spotter report (Bruce Donaldson) of 53mm in 21 minutes at Kahibah, just southwest of the Newcastle CBD. This easily exceeds flash flood thresholds. Maximum wind gust estimated at 85km/h (not severe).
SES/Newcastle Herald reports that the Westfield Kotara carpark flooded after a heavy rain storm, with 30 cars inundated. The shopping centre was evacuated. No figures given for rainfall.

51mm recorded at Blacktown on a hydrology gauge. This was the highest rainfall total in the Sydney basin, and radar analysis shows that this would have fallen in about 90 minutes.This rate is on the flash flooding threshold.
65mm recorded in an hour at Mangrove Mountain AWS, including a period of 34mm in 10 minutes. This easily exceeds flash flood criteria.

Spotter report (Brian Byles) of 91mm from thunderstorms in >4 hours. Spotter reports that he did not observe the end time of the storm, but anaysis of the radar shows that the majority of this rain would have fallen in about 2 hours, easily reaching flash flood criteria. This report also included a damaging wind gust.
52mm recorded in half an hour at Dooralong, on the Central Coast. This exceeds flash flood criteria.
70mm recorded in 30 minutes at the Gears hydrology gauge on the Wyong River, with 90mm in total. This is approximately a 1 in 100 year rainfall rate.
Spotter report (Brian Byles) of an estimated 90 km/h wind gust from the SW associated with a thunderstorm. This report also included heavy rain.
49 knot wind gusts recorded from a thunderstorm at Kiama AWS.

Spotter report (Doug Banks) of flash flooding in Broken Hill, with roads flooded in town. Rainfall recorded was only 10.7mm in 2 hours, but this was probably not representative of the heaviest rain. Spotter reported a large amount of raised dust embedded in the early part of the storm, with wind gusts estimated to 60km/h from the NE.
91.2mm recorded in 2 hours at Ballina Airport AWS from a morning thunderstorm, including 65mm in half an hour. These rates easily exceed flash flooding thresholds.
Media and SES reports of widespread damage in the Mullaway/Woolgoolga/Arrawarra area, with trees down, powerlines down, roofs blown off and windows blown in. No estimates of gust strength available.
Media and SES reports of damage due to damaging wind gusts from a thunderstorm, with broken windows and large trees down in the Nambucca Heads region. No estimate of gust strength available.
Spotter report of 10c piece sized hail at Grose Vale, to the west of Richmond.
66mm recorded from an early morning thunderstorm at Bungwahl in two hours on a hydrology gauge. This exceeds flash flood criteria.
Spotter report of 4cm hail near Pokolbin, in the Hunter Valley.
2cm hail reported from Lochivar, near Maitland in the Hunter Valley.

Spotter report (Gary Duckett) from Gosforth of 5cm hail, with the most common size being 4.5cm. Hail path was about 500m wide, with a fairly sparse distribution of 10 hailstones per 5 metres squared. Not much rain, and no wind. Damage included dented cars and knocked branches. A green rotating wall cloud was observed ahead of the onset of the storm.
Spotter report (Liz Pralica) of hail 2cm in diameter at Clarence Town, in the Hunter Valley, with the most common sized stone being 1cm. This report also included heavy rainfall.

40mm in 30 minutes recorded on a hydrology gague from a thunderstorm at Nabiac. This amount exceeds flash flooding thresholds.

The passage of a cold front produced several strong wind gusts along the west coast and heavy rainfall about the southwest corner. The rainfall recorded at Teds Pool reached an Average Recurrence Interval of between 1 in 20- 50 years. The rainfall recorded at Brennans Ford reached an ARI of between 1 and 10-20 years. DFES received numerous calls for help mostly for water damage and inundation.

A tornado was also reported in the southeast suburbs of Perth, where significant structural damage occurred.%D %D The second, and strongest, clod front moved over the southwest region in the early hours of Sunday the 23rd. This front was associated with a low that was analysed as low as 959hPa. The peak Geraldton to Albany pressure difference was observed at 21.7hPa which was the strongest since the event of 28 Novemeber 2012, and strongest winter event since a delta of 21.9hPa was observed on 10 June 2012. Widespread damaging winds were experienced over the SWLD with severe gusts recoreded at many locations.

Continuing, widespread humidity over the southern half of the state, combined with a west coast trough led to an unstable airmass over the western Gascoyne and much of the SWLD. Early low-level dry air caused suppression of convection until mid to late afternoon. By 3pm, thunderstorms had started over much of the northern part of the area, and soon after extended to the southern half of the Central West. Initially, a Severe Thunderstorm Warning covered parts of the Gascoyne and Central West, but this was extended south to cover the Perth Metro and Mandurah after 3:30pm.%D %D While no observations of severe phenomena were observed for this event, radar indications strongly suggested severe thunderstorms occurred in the warning zone at times during the day. In the northern half of the warning area, storms around the Three Peaks township displayed VIL peaks of greater than 60kg/m2 (suggesting hail >= 2cm). Further south, a supercell developed near Yanchep with VIL peaks of greater than 110kg/m2. The widespread activity in the south generated a cold pool, which suppressed further storm activity; the STW for the Perth Metro was cancelled at 6:30pm. Storms continued further north until the STW cancellation at 11:30pm.%D %D

Afternoon thunderstorm activity continued in the Gascoyne which produced heavy rainfall. Lyons River crossing recorded 53.6 mm in a 24 hour period which at times reached an ARI of betwen 10 and 20 years. Minnie Creek Airstrip recorded 54.2mm in a 24 hour period which at times reached an ARI of between 5 and 10 years.%D %D                                            Prcp      Perd                                                               %D Station Name          Stn no Date          (mm)  QF (days)                                                              %D -------------------- ------- ----------- ------ --- ------                                                              %D PARABURDOO AERO       007185 07-Mar-2015   55.8  00      1                                                              %D MININER               007177 07-Mar-2015   55.6  00      1                                                              %D MINNIE CREEK AIRSTRI  006104 07-Mar-2015   54.2  00      1                                                              %D LYONS RIVER CROSSING  506013 07-Mar-2015   53.6  00      1                                                              %D YINNETHARRA CROSSING  507000 07-Mar-2015   53.6  00      1                                                              %D WITTENOOM             005026 07-Mar-2015   52.8  00      1                                                              %D

Marginal severe thunderstorm at Amberley produced only minor damage with broken tree branches.
One house in Ipswich and a hall in Rathdowney suffered roof damage.  Several power lines were brought down.  An anemometer positioned 45ft above the ground recorded a 55 knot gust.

Several observers reported seeing a waterspout off the Gold Coast between Burleigh Heads and Surfers Paradise at about 4:45pm.  The waterspout disturbed the water surface quite markedly.  The funnel extended from a cumulus cloud.  Thunderstorms were actually just west of the coast at the time.  The funnel lasted for about 10 minutes.

A line of thunderstorm moved over the Gold Coast produced wind damage in Southport.  A 20 ton yacht residing at the Southport Yacht Club was blown off its cradle landing on its side and crushing a wire security fence.
Two houses partially unroofed in Brisbane's inner southern suburbs.  Also several large trees blown down.

Wind damage along the path of the storm extending from Ipswich to Redcliffe with the worst damage occurring at Redcliffe.  At least 500 homes in the Redcliffe area suffered structural dmage with many losing their roofs.  The Redcliffe Aero suffered massive losses as hangars were damaged and light planes flipped over.  Maximum wind gust at Brisbane Airport was 38 knots, 56 knots was recorded at Archerfield and 100 knots at recorded on an anemometer on a yacht in Redcliffe.

Three tornado or waterspouts were sighted by several Redcliffe residents.  Two were not reaching the ground, but it is expected the third may two touchdowns, one in the Bayside suburb of Clontarf and the other near the Redcliffe Aero Club. Large amount of damage at both sites.
Maximum thunderstorm induced wind gust at Mt Isa.  Previous record was 68 knots which occurred on 17 October 1971.  Unroofed some houses, upturned several light aircraft and downed power lines.

The estimated damage bill of the storm was about $1 million.  Some structural damage to properties, major damage to trees and vegetation, one transmission tower blown down which was designed to withstand winds of up to 110 knots.
Egg size hail smashed windows and damaged cars.
Reference to flash flooding in the suburbs of Brisbane, but no rainfall figures.
An observer at oakey reported wind gusts of about 45 knots.
Strong winds reported at Geebung but no reports of any severe damage.  A gust of 70 knots was recorded at Kingscliff south of the Queensland Border.
Widespread hail across the suburbs.  Marble size hail and heavy rain reported at Aspley, hail at Bracken Ridge and Geebung.  Cricket ball size hail at Murwillumbah south of the Queensland Border.
Maximum wind gust recorded at Amberley was 42 knots.  Generally only minor damage reported with minimal roof damage to 6 houses, and power disruptions.
Marble size hail was reported from Margate and Laidley to the west of Ipswich. Pea size hail was also reported between Ipswich and Hattonvale and at Albany Creek but only minor damage.

Gusts were estimated at about 80 knots from reliable observers.  One catamaran was overturned and several other boats broke from their moorings.  A roll cloud was observed by the weathe observers at Maroochydore airport.
Wind brought down power lines, causing disruptions to power supplies to about 500 homes.  One house lost its roof and a recreation hall was badly damaged.
Hail to cricket ball size in Booval with a fibro roof damaged.  Hail caused forest damage through Samford and Ferny Grove.  Golf ball size hail reported in Collingwood Park with 12 homes damaged.
Winds of up to 36 knots were reported at RAAF Amberley, but little damage directly attributed to the wind.
Hail up to golf ball in size caused damage to 27 homes in the Ipswich Booval areas.  Power lines were brought down causing cuts in power supplies to 2100 homes.

Residents reported golf ball size hail causing minor damage to property with a few broken windows etc, but extensive crop damage.  Rain caused flash flooding in some areas but rainfall totals did not exceed the one in ten year event.

A newly renovated home was completely destroyed and five others lost their roofs as a result of the storm.  One strom spotter reported the cloud rotating and possibly a funnel cloud.  It was described as one of the worst wind storms experienced in the area.
The storm spotter at 'Glen Idyle' a property in Harrisville reported hail up to 3cm in diameter but no reports of any hail related damage.

The thunderstorm was most severe over northern New South Wales with extensive damage to property.  Damage on the Gold Coast was generally minor with roof tiles being moved out of place and minor tree damage.  Winds to 65 knots were recorded on the Gold Coast
Several houses unroofed.  Maximum wind gust of 47 knots at Brisbane Airport.
Strong winds unroofed 3 houses and blew several steel sheds away.

Maximum wind gust at Brisbane Airport was 29 knots, but damage suggests possible wind gusts stronger than this.  Trees were brought down, and at least 30 homes suffered roof damage in the Albert Shire and on the Gold Coast.

Max wind gusts recorded at Coolangatta AWS and Amberley RAAF Base were 55 knots and 48 knots respectively.  Two aircraft were flipped over by the wind at Coolangatta Airport.  Several houses suffered roof damage with fallen tress on the Gold Coast, Beaudesert and Wynnum.
Wind gusts of up to 60 knots partially unroofed several homes, brought down trees and power lines and caused power disruptions to Toowoomba and surrounding areas.
Golf ball size hail was reported to have fallen in northwest parts of Gatton, but is reported to have caused little damage.
Intense rain caused flash flooding in the region.  Rainfall exceeds the one in ten year event
Hailstones as large as cricket balls left a damage path about 4 kilometres wide.  Crops due for harvesting were almost completely destroyed and trees were stripped of their leaves.

Maximum wind gust reported at Archerfield, Southport AWS and Amberly were 55, 55 and 50 knots respectively.  Many homes suffered severe wind damage.  The worst affected areas on the coast were Tweed heads and Nerang, and in Brisbane were Acacia Ridge, Balmoral, Wishart and Sunnybank Hills where many homes lost their roofs.  Power lines were brought down by fallen trees causing power outages to more than 17,000 homes.

Golf ball size hail in the Coolangatta -Tweed Heads area produced up to $900,000 damage to car yard dealers.  Many house windows were broken.  Hail to pea size was also reported in the Brisbane suburbs.

The roof of a shopping centre in Nambour and several attractions at the Big Pineapple suffered wind damage.  Otherwise several trees blown over and power disruptions to resident on the Sunshine coast.
Slow moving thunderstorm cell produced heavy rainfall around laidley causing flash flooding in the Laidley Creek.

Tennis ball size hail reported in Lowood causing extensive car and house damage.  Windows were smashed and water tanks were pierced.  The cell split near Lowood with the one cell moving to the southeast and producing  golf ball size hail over Beaudesert and marble size hail at Ipswich.  The northern moving cell passed over the sunshine coast with reports of small hail.

Damage spread across southern and northern suburbs, in particular, Kington, Capalaba, Holland Park, Mt Gravatt, Jindalee and Sinnamon Park.  A number of houses unroofed, or suffering roof damage resulting from fallen trees.  Major power blackouts in southern and southwest suburbs.
Marble or pea size hail was reported in the southwest suburbs, but no reports of major damge.

Thunderstorm produced strong winds causing damage to more than 200 homes.  Most of the damage was a result of fallen trees.  20 caravans were destroyed, with another 25 with minor damages.  Several yachts were blown off their cradles in the marina's dry storage area.
Wind brought down power lines and caused power supply disruption to many homes in the northen and southern suburbs.  30 homes suffered minor damage in the Pine Rivers area.
Ragged marble size hail reported in Aspley and Kenmore.  Caused no major damage.

A peak gust of 41 knots wa recorded at the Mt isa MIO at 02:17 and by the account of damage caused by wind and by observation of staff this may well have been around the maximum wind gust around the city area also.  Mt Isa Mines weather equipment was inoperable at the time.

Severe Flooding to several commercial centres, with the Electirical Store being the worst affected.  The MIO at the airport recorded a rainfall rate of 48mm/hr during the peak rain perioed.  The quality control station at Mt Isa Mines recorded a rate of about 100 mm/hr exceeding the one in ten year rainfall rate for Mt Isa.
Peter Burn from Rockhampton Met Office reported large jagged edged hail.
Up to egg size hail reported in the Narangba, Caboolture area causing damage to 24 homes and several vehicles. A numbers of vans were damaged in several caravan parks.

Extensive damage over a wide area of the Gold Coast with the worst affected area being Benowa.  In total approximately 250 houses suffered damage of some kind.  Also major wind damage to several  shopping centres including the main beach shopping centre and Pacific Fair at Broadbeach.  A high rise penthouse suffered at least $300,000 worth of damage as a window was blown in, balcony railings snapped off, with glass and pot plants being blown to the ground.  Several caravans in the Broadbeach and Main Beach caravan parks were blown over.  Widespread power outages along the coast.
Intense rainfall and hail causing several  commercial building roofs to collapse.  One person was injured as his workshop roof fell in.

One house was totally unroofed in the Slacks Creek area.  Severeal houses in Sunnybank Hills and Forrestdale suffered minor roof damage with loosened tiles etc.  A large gum tree fell on the roof of a house in Rochedale causing extensive damge.  Damage was generally confined to very small  pockets across the suburbs with only severe dmage to very few houses.  This was mostly caused by weak construction or trees.
One house was unroofed and several trees uprooted and stripped.  A four tonne feed bin had been picked up and blown about 10 metres.  Only a maximum wind gust of 19 knots was recorded at Oakey.
Golf ball size hail which took at least two and a half hours to melt.  One property owner lost 9 acrres of barley due to hail damage.
Balckwater hospital was unroofed. one house damaged and widespread tree damage.
Some wind damage in the Shailer park region, but the main disruption was the loss of power to about 66,000 homes in the southern suburbs and Gold Coast areas.
Pea size hail reported in the Shailer Park area, but no evidence of associated damage.

Main damage in the Glenwood area.  3 houses suffered partial or nearly full unroofing.  1 house under construction was damaged beyond repair.  Major damage path was about 20 kilometres long and half a kilometre wide.  At Gympie, one house was completely unroofed and several others lost loose sheets of iron.
Extensive hail damage to crops and vegetation in the region.
A thunderstorm produced a measured 70 knot gust at Svennsons Beach on Great Keppel Island.  These are know to be pretty reliable observations.

No damage at Roma.  One house completely unroofed at Yarrawonga, and 6 houses usffered moderate to severe roof damage at Yuleba.  High tension power lines between Yuleba and Taroom were blown down.  Double stand metal road signs were bent to 90 degrees by the wind, or broken off.
Max wind gust of 50 knots reported at Rockhampton Met Office, with max gust of 54 knots at Moura Mines.  Gust front was accompanied by a roll cloud.

Major building damage to shops, a block of units, Caravan Park and a resort. 25 houses and 12 commercial premises suffered damage or were unroofed. The fire station was demolished, and outbuildings in the Torquay school ground were damaged.  Several houses were damaged with the falling of large trees.
Two school children struck by lightning and killed as they were bushwalking in the Lamington National Park.

Maximum wind gust recorded at Bureau of Meteorology Office at Mt Isa was 41 knots, but max wind gusts of 89 knots were recorded at Mt Isa Mines.  $30,000 damage was caused to buildings at the Junior Soccer club.  A caravan was substantially damaged and a garden shed nearby was flattened.  Two portable housing blocks, used as dressing sheds were also damaged.  One of the sheds, weighing 4.5 tonne was lifted off its supports and carried 20 metres into a fence.
1 house at Ebenezer and another near Ipswich were unroofed.  Seven other houses suffered roof damage resulting from fallen trees.
Golf ball size hail reported at Ipswich and Leichardt.  A fibro roof was holed by hail.
Very large hail reported by Oakey observer, no records of any damage.

Hail reported from several cells between Brisbane and Rockhampton, but only the cell near Kingaroy and Pittsworth produced any damage.  Hail produced damage to cotton in Pittsworth and brought down power lines in Kingaroy.
Golf ball size hail caused damage to 300 ha of crops including vegetables and apples and stone fruit orchards.  The cost of damage is estimated to be between $5,000,000 and $7,000,000.
Winds produced structural damage to at least 50 homes in Brisbane['s northern suburbs with the worst affected regions beng Bracken Ridge, Albany Creek, Sandgate, Deagon and Brighton.

Damage to a least 100 homes in the Carrara, Boonooroo Park, Ashmore Benow and Runaway Bay area.  About 8 houses were severely damaged with trees crashing onto roofs.  Thick trees were snapped, fences and pergolas demolished and roof tiles broken.
Six houses in Boondall were damaged by falling trees and flying debris.
Winds caused structural damage to 2 residences and out buildings.  Several trees were uprooted.
Only small hail which did not cause any damage.
Max gust 55 knots but no damage reported.
Structural damage to 27 homes, with one house completely unroofed.  12,000 homes suffered power losses.  Several trees were broken or blown down.
A woman was struck by lightning as she lent against a downpipe.
Intense rainfall caused flash flooding in the Booval area exceeding the one in ten year rainfall.
Pea size hail reported at Mt Cootha,  golf ball size hail reported at Caboolture.
Intense rainfall caused flash flooding in the region.
At least 12 homes suffered roof damage and more than 7000 homes were without power.
Intense rainfall over an hour, exceeding the one in ten year rainfall threshold.
Several thunderstorms during the day from about 3 pm until 11:45 pm with the maximum wind gust of 47 knots occurring at 10:45 pm.
Rainfall exceed the one in 10 year rainfall event.
7 houses were unroofed and several trees suffering broken limbs.
Strong winds only lasted about a minute as described by local residents.  Minor wind damage to several houses and trees in fairly localized area.
Large hail experienced in Brisbane's northern suburbs causing minor structural damage, including damage to Strathpine Shopping Centre.
Wind caused damage to 11 buildings with at least two buildings unroofed.
Golf ball size hail was reported causing severe damage to local crops.

Short-duration heavy rainfall resulted in flash flooding in local creeks,  Some roads were cut with one property remaining inaccessible for at least 18 hours.  In the Ma Ma Creek region a large catchment area on a steep slope funnelled water into a narrow area causing significant soil losses and damage to irrigation equipment.
21:00 UTC Metar from Jackson Airport recorded a maximum wind gust of 56 knots, with only 2 mm of rainfall.  Also a large amount of dust.
Dry microburst.  Little precipitation..
Several houses suffered minor wind damage.  Insurance assessor advised there was damage to 20 homes in the Karana Downs area. Max gust was recorded at Amberly.
Short lived heavy shower.
Several houses in the Zillmere to Shorncliffe area suffered minor wind damage.  Many branches blown down.
Pea size hail Zillmere to Shorncliffe.
Wind damage to sugar cane crops and farm outbuildings.  Also minor wind damage to housing and flora.  SES reported lifting a fallen tree off a carport.

Golf ball size hail was reported in the Pioneer Valley region just to the west of Mackay.  Hail was also reported at Buchasia to the north of Mackay, though no detail on size was provided.  Main damage to sugar grain crops.
Several reports of short period heavy rainfall in the area.  No reports of local flooding.
Cell produced tennis ball size hail in Marlborough causing damage to cars and windows.  The hail produced a hole in the wall of the local SHELL service station.

Several reports of heavy rainfall in the area between Mt Morgan and Biloela.  Highest total was 150 mm in the Fiveways Goovigen area which according to radar imagery fell in approximately a 2-hour period.
Extensive damage to Paw Paw and Mango crops on 7 farms.
Thunderstorm described as a "mini tornado" though no reported sightings of a funnel.  Trees were blown down and part of a school was destroyed.
Reports of hail with the storm though no specific reports of hail damage or hail size.

Golf ball size hail was observed from Upper Coomera to Runaway Bay.  The hail caused extensive damage to cars, and trees, with minor damage to houses.  The cell passed directly over Movie World damaging lighting and trees within the park and every car in the car park.   Trees were heavily stripped killing several birds. and many houses in Helensvale, Runaway Bay area suffered damage to skylights.  Major hail damage to several car yards stretching from Helensvale down to Southport.
Native trees with trunks 20 to 27 centimetres in diameter were snapped.  Winds destroyed a garden shed and pergola, and caused thousands of dollars worth of damage to the local nursery.
Hail damage to cars and houses piercing windows and roof iron.

There were no anemometers in the immediate area and the type of damage made estimating  wind speeds difficult. Only one house was damaged directly by the wind (unroofed) other damage was cuased by falling tree limbs.
Eyewitness quote from Courier Mail " There were trees falling all around my head  and the hail was so thick I couldn't get back in the house."

Eyewitnesses reported extensive wind damage both to dwellings and trees.  The damage was such that  it was estimated that gusts must have exceeded 100km/h. Wind came initially from the southeast but backed to the northeast without weakening.
Pea to marble size hail accompanied the onset of  extemely strong swirling wind gusts and lasted until the onset of rain.
OBSERVERS OF THE APPROACHING STORM COMMENTED THAT THE CLOUD HAD A DISTINCTIVE GREENISH TINGE AND WAS ACCOMPANIED BY FREQUENT BOLTS OF FORKED LIGHTNING.
VERY  INTENSE RAINFALL ACCOMPANIED THE STORM AND SHOWERY CONDITIONS CONTRINUED FOR THE REST OF THE DAY
Mean wind estimated by farmers to be 70km/h
Quote from the "Rockhampton Morning Bulletin  of 03/11/94.
GUST WAS NOT MEASURED OR MENTIONED MAIN EMPHASIS ON HAIL
TENNIS BALL SIZE HAIL DAMAGED CAR WINDSCREENS, PUNCHED HOLES IN THE ASBESTOS  CEMENT WALLS OF THE SHELL SERVICE STATION AND BROKE WINDOWS IN THE TOWN HALL.
Winds of up to 50 knots (93 kilometres per hour). Gargett one tree blown over,
HAIL STONES THE SIZE OF GOLF BALLS WERE REPORTED IN MARANI, GARGETT AND SEPTIMUS.
MANY RESIDENTS THROUGHOUT THE PIONEER VALLEY REPORTED FIERCE THUNDER AND LIGHTNING ACTIVITY...

GUST WAS STRONG ENOUGH TO MAKE A TIED DOWN AIRCRAFT BECOME AIRBOURNE AND TO TURN GRAVEL INTO MISSILES WHICH MADE IT TOO DANGEROUS TO MOVE.  wIND TURNED A CARAVAN OVER AND CAUSED STRUCTURAL DAMAGE TO BUILDINGS.  THE WIDTH OF THE DESTRUCTIVE PATH WAS APPROXIMATELY 300 TO 500 METRES.

13.4 MM RAINFALL  ACTUALLY MEASURED HOWEVER  THE ACTUAL RAINFALL  WAS  ESTIMATED AT 25MM BECAUSE THE  RAIN WAS BEING BLOWN HORIZONTALLY BY THE STRONG WINDS.  WIDTH OF AREA AFFECTED BY RAINFALL IS APPROXIMATELY 1 KILOMETER.
HIGH WINDS SNAPPED GUM TREES LIKE TOOTHPICKS.
No  damage was reported .
MAXIMUM GUST 260/49 KNOTS AT 0535UTC
HAIL WAS MENTIONED IN A REPORT IN THE LONGREACH "LEADER".  SEE CONVERDSATION WITH MR WITTAKER.
TERRIFYING WIND RIPPED OUT 50FT + REDGUM IN OUR FRONT YARD,LOTS OF OTHER TREES (SMALL IN BACK YARD)
IT WAS ESTIMATED BY OTHERS 7 INCHES OF RAIN FELL AS MOST OF IT WAS HORIZONTAL DRIVING RAIN.
THIS DOES NOT APPEAR TO BE A THUNDERSTORM RELATED EVENT. THE FACT THAT IT OCCURED IN THE EARLY MORNING MADE EYEWITNESS ACCOUNTS OF THE PHENOMENA IMPOSSIBLE TO OBTAIN.
THIS DID NOT APPEAR TO BE A TORNADO AS SUCH  SOME POSSIBILITIES ARE A WATER SPOUT COME ASHORE OR A MICROBURST.
The rainfall during this storm was estimated at between 35 and 50mm
STRONG WIND GUSTS OCCURRED AT THE AIRPORT AND NOT IN TOWN.

A HOUSEHOLDER LOCATED AT THE CORNER OF MAIN AVENUE AND DILKERA STREET BALMORAL WHOSE HOUSE WAS UNROOFED REPORTED INTENSE PEA SIZE HAIL STRIKING HIS WEST FACING WINDOWS ALMOST AT THE ONSET OF THE STORM.

A GUST OF 53 KNOTS WAS RECORDED AT 12:53UTC  ON 29TH AT BRISBANE AIRPORT RADAR SITE. AN ANEMOMETER BELONGING TO S.E.Q.E.B. AND LOCATED AT THE DEPOT IN BOWEN BRIDGE ROAD AT VICTORIA PARK RECORDED A GUST OF 47 KNOTS  AT 12:38
6 HOUSES IN REDWOOD CIRCLE BLACKWOOD RD AREA OF CEDAR GROVE DAMAGED. EXTENSIVE DAMAGE TO TREES.  CROPS WIPPED OUT.
No reports of damage
Pea sized hail  observed,  wind gust caused no damage.
Golf ball size hail caused extensive damage to new and used cars.  The cricket test match was delayed for over an hour.
Severe squalls caused damage to more than 30 aircraft with an estimated cost of $300,000
Hail up to Cricket ball in size caused extensive house and car damge.
No actual wind gust reports, but extensive damage and the development of a tornado.
Golf ball size hail caused damage to cars and houses with broken windows and smashed roof tiles.

Tornado left a discontinuous path of destruction through sparsely populated country. One brick house was completely destroyed.  Three cattle were destroyed after sustaining injury from flying debris.  Large area of pine plantation flattened.
Hail up to cricket ball in size was observed at four locations in the storm's path from Bullyard to Bundaberg.

Severe wind damage was sustained in the Bullyard to Bundaberg area.  At least nine houses were extensivly damaged or destroyed in the Bucca area by a tornado.  About 20 cattle had to be destroyed after sustaining injury from flying debris.  Stones were embedded in trees.  A picture frame in one house was imbedded in the opposite wall and the body of a 3 tonne truck was carried about 300 metres.

Torndao observed and photographed in the Bucca- Kolan area caused extensive property and flora damage.  20 cattle were killed or had to be destroyed.  One eyewitness observed severeal touch downs of the tornado.

Hail up to golf ball in size damaged roofs, dented and smashed car windows.  About half of the Booval shopping centre suffered damage after hail blocked guttering and rain overflowed into the complex's internal roofing panels.   Both stock and fittings were damaged with estimated costs of about $750,000.  Marble size hail was reported from the Kenmore area, and pea size hail at Bardon.

Gust recorded at Cape Moreton AWS exceeds the Severe Thunderstorm Definition gust threshold.  No report of wind damage in the area.  Strong winds were also reported from the Ipswich area with trees and powerlines brought down.  No anemometer in the area.

Hail up to Tennis ball in size ripped through the town of Bauple destroying crops and damaging property.  Roofs were damaged, car windows smashed etc.  The hail smashed through $40,000 worth of hail netting at one property destroying the Persimmon crop.  Ironically, hail of similar size hit the farm before hence the reason for the hail netting.
Second hailstorm to hit Bauple in an hour.  The storm produced golf ball size hail, but it is difficult to ascertain damage relative to the second storm after the passage of the first storm.
Several strom spotters in the Gympie region reported very strong winds associated with the storm, but apart from minor foliage damage, no other damage was reported.
Severe Thunderstorm passed through the Gympie district with many areas suffering damage as a result of golf ball size hail.  Crops at Glastonbury through Gympie to Curra were destroyed.
Gusts to 51 knots at Rockhampton WSO.  No reports of damage.
Hailstones caused widespread damage to wheat and cotton crops.  Loss on the crop yield estimated to be about $38,000
Residents estimated wind gusts to 40 kmph.  Causing generally minor damage to foliage and property.
Report of golf ball size hail that shattered as it hit the ground.  No reports of hail induced damage.

Strong winds caused damage to both property and trees.  A number of large pine trees were uprooted and blown over.  A numbe of caravans were damaged mainly by falling debris.  A steel canopy supported by 4" by 4" wooden posts was peeled off and the posts broken.  Damage path about 10 to 15 metres wide.
Golf ball size hail caused damage to crops and property in the region.

Strong winds caused property and foliage damage.  Trees were blown onto powerlines causing major blackouts through the southern suburbs of Brisbane.  Several homes suffered roof damage with one house in Browns Plains was completely blown off.  One resident described the storm as spiralling down the street, but no evidence of a funnel.

Up to cricket ball size hail fell over several suburbs between Ipswich and Bellbowrie causing extensive roof damage through the area.  Many cars suffered major damage to hail dents and smashed windows.   Power supplies were disrupted to about 9500 homes.  No estimate to date of the damage bill.  Actual footage of the event caught on home video.

A non-severe thunderstorm cell passed over Brisbane Airport and Nudgee Beach during the early afternoon.  A fisherman in his boat about 300 metres from shore was struck by lightning and killed as the cell passed over.
Up to golf ball size hail at Ubobo, Nagorrin and surrounding areas.  No damage reports received.
Storm spotter reported rainfall total of 65mm in 45 minutes.  No reports of flash flooding

Hail up to cricket ball in size reported from Palmwoods, with hail to the size of golf balls  between Maleny and Maroochydore.  Hail damage to fruit trees in the Palmwoods area with avocadoes stripped of developing fruit.
Thunderstorm produced hail up to the size of a $2 coin.  No reports of any damage associated with the event.

Storm produced severe wind gusts which destroyed several houses and unroofed at least six others.  The roof of a recently built petrol station was damaged.  Damaged was blown about 200 - 300 metres.  The path of destruction was very narrow, approximatly 50 metres.
A line of thunderstorm moving east across the district produced rainfalls exceeding the one in ten year hourly rainfall intensities.

A flying instructor reported seeing what he described as the beginning of a tornado funnel emerging from the base of a cumulonimbus cloud.  He estimated that the protruberence extended 200 metres from the base of the cloud and lasted about 7 metrres.  The funnel did not reach the ground.
No imformation on damage.
Event reported from ABC News.  No information on damage caused.
No gust strength reported, but one house completely unroofed.
Hail reported, but no size provided.
Wind gusts damaged caravans, houses and knocked down trees and powerlines.

Severe property and foliage damage through the town.  The roof of the Blackwater Hospital was severely damaged and patients had to be transferred to the Emerald hospital.  Sixteen provate dwellings and 6 commercial buildings suffered roof damage.  Two schools and the public library were partially unroofed.  The town's power supply was cut for at least 12 hours.  Major damage at the local caravan park with wind blowing vans from sites and ripping annexes.  Almost every tree in the caravan park was blown down.  The Duaringa Shire was declared a disaster area by the Minister for Emergency Services.
Wind gust to 42 knots at Amberley.  No damge reported.

Rainfall intensities exceeding the one in ten year hourly rainfall figure in the southwest suburbs of Brisbane, particularly Kenmore, Archerfield, Sunnybank and also in the Bayside suburbs of Wynnum and Manly.
Widespread damage to fruit crops.
No reports of damage in the area.

Property damage, mostly house roofs in the Logan, Beenleigh and Beaudesert areas.  Trees and powerlines were brought down and at least 50,000 people were without power.  Four flying foxes were  killed when wind detroyed their cages.  Wind gusts from recording sites at Coolangatta and Cape Moreton of up to 60 knots.
No reports of damage.  Wind gusts greater than 50 knots over a period of 15 minutes.
No reports of damage in the area, but 55 knots recorded.

SES reported 15 requests for help in the Beenleigh area.  There were also 10 properties damaged at Logan, roof damage to one house in Beaudesert, and damage to several properties in the Redland Bay area.
Small hail reported in the inner Brisbane suburb of Stones Corner, with only minor damage.
No reports of damage received.
Strong winds brought down trees and powerlines.
Hail up to cricket ball size damaged property and trees, piercing holes through roofs, and windows and denting cars.  Damage to cars in a Morayfield caryard is estimated to be $2 million.

Isolated pockets of damage throughout the district.  One house was partially unroofed in Baralaba, and another in Dingo, both outside the Capricornia district.  Within the Capricornia district, some property at Thangool, Mt Morgan, Gracemere and Yeppoon also suffered damage.
Unofficial recording from Keppel Sands coast guard.
Strong wind gust on the northeast side of town.  Some roof damage and large trees down.Max gust at Mt Isa M.O. 36 kts from SSW.
Only mushy pea size hail with no damage as a result.
Observer at Rockhampton WSO sighted a suspected tornado.  Funnel passed over a sparsely populated area and as a result no reports of damage or confirmation.

Severe wind gusts associated with the line of thunderstorms were reported from several locations in the Gold Coast Hinterland in the Numinbah Valley region.  Chiefly roof damage to houses and trees down.  Based on max gust of 46 knots on the coast, and the fact that the more intense part of the line of storms was situated over the Hinterland gusts are estimated to have exceeded 55 knots.
Hail up to golf ball in size resulted in local damage in the Rathdowney area with some windows smashed.
A few houses suffered roof damage.  Trees and powerlines were brought down with loss of power to more than 24000 homes in the coast and metropolitan region
Wind gust to 34 knots at Brisbane Airport from the same line of storms.  Branches broken from trees, otherwise little damage.
Radar indicates the line of thunderstorms in the Double Island Point area at this time, but the storms looked particularly weaker.
Nil reports of damage, but reports of wind gusts associated with the storms.
Reports of severe wind gusts, caused damage to several properties.
Hail reported to have fallen in the area, but no indication of size, which probably indicates it was not particularly large.
Storm spotter estimated gusts to 44 knots.  No damage reported.
Two storm spotter reports of hail in the area, the first report describing hail up to the size of a $2 coin and the second observing golf ball size hail but not damage.
Professional Mariner reported 50 knot Gusts.  Many trees down in the southern suburbs from Karana Downs to Southern Moreton Bay.  Three houses suffered roof damage in the southern suburbs.

Report from Joe Courtney in WA whose parents live in Wamuran.  Strong wind gusts accompanied the storm with two paths of damage.  Large trees were down while adjacent smaller ones were untouched.  No structures received damage.
Storm spotter reported strong wind gusts uprooting and breaking limbs from trees.
Hail up to marble size observed, but fell for only a very short time.  No damage as a consequence.
Significant rainfall which just exceeds the one in ten year rainfall amounts.
Wind gusts to 51 knots recorded at Mt Isa WSO.  No reports of structural damage in town.
Reports of strong wind gusts but no damage.
Storm spotter reported estimated wind gusts to 55 knots.  Some properties suffered minor roof damage, but generally damage was restricted to trees.
Trees blown down in the Maleny-Landsborough area.  No structural damage to properties but generally a sparsely populated area.
Rainfall at Woodford exceeding the one in ten year rainfall amount.
Yepoon AWS 43 kts. Great Keppel Is estimated gust 54kts. Rockhampton AMO Technical Officer estimated W to SW gusts of 40 to 50 kts at Yepoon.

Damage to several houses. 1 house lost roof, owner estimated damage at $7000

First storm at 07.30am precipitated 40mm in 20 minutes. Spotter also reported a friend, living 1 km NW, recorded 105 mm from the same storm.

column9: Wind 330/15 gust 38 kts at 0637 utc
Rainfall between 40 and 50 mm was reported over 1.5 to 2 hours.

YEML AWS was knocked out at the start of the event. However there were 2 rports of "mini tornadoes" and a Circus tent was shreded with internal poles broken. Power lines were knocked down with reports of some minor house damage.

Toolara AWS wind 360/37 knots gusts 49 knots. A Glastonbury man's caravan was blown to pieces, and other homes were damaged with a steel framed shed demolished and belongings and debris scattered over several hectares.

Very strong winds were reported beteewn Innot Hot Springs and the Silver valley Road west of Wild River. The storm damage was over an area of approx 10 square km with wind damage apparant from a variety of directions. Trees were defoliated and trunks snapped off well above the ground. A house was de-roofed with the corrigated iron found a considerable distance away. The storm was described as being like a mini tornado.
Reports of up to 5 tornadoes in the Rockhampton area, with the Bureau only confirming 1 possibly 2 at this stage.
A report of 72mm of rain in an hour was received

Damage to trees in a 2km by 200m wide area at Murphy's Creek. (Trees to 30m high). A car port was lifted and thrown 60m with the concrete footings still attached. Farm sheds were damaged. In Toowoomba, 14 houses were attended to by SES with mainly trees on roofs or through windows. Oakey reported winds 130/31 kts gusts 46 kts at 0911utc and Toowoomba reported gusts to 36 kts from 0834utc to 0909 utc (wind 120/23kts)
Report of 50mm of rain in 1/2 hr in Toowoomba.65mm of rain in under 1/2hr measured in a rain guage on a Murphy Creek property.
20 cent piece to golf ball sized hail was reported in Murphys Creek
Wind gust brought large trees down, with a stable losing its roof as well as part of a house's roof. Damage to crops was reported from Cunninghams gap
A man was electrocuted in Cleveland when falling branches brought down power lines. Gusts brought trees down, lifted tiles and blew a shed approx 15 m
Spotter reported 38mm in 1/2 hr, with storm water drains overflowing.

Established trees were uprooted and stripped of leaves, power poles were blown over and property damged with 2 houses demolished and six caravans damaged or destroyed by winds. Most of the damage was laid in one direction with no discernible evidence of wind rotation.
A number of reports of hail across the Herbert-Burdekin region.
More than 26200 lightening strikes were recorded within one hour, associated with a series of storms in the region, resulting in widespread damage to the electricity grid.
There were several phone reports of sightings of a funnel cloud, though nothing has been confirmed tornadic.
Many trees were snapped in half. (One had a diameter of 2 feet). All trees were aligned in the same direction. Canungra Valley Vineyards suffered damage to netting.
The majority of damage reported was mainly water damage caused by local flash flooding. Record of 55.8 mm in 33min at Airport

Flash flooding. Gold Coast was the first affected by intense rainfall, followed shortly after by Brisbane City.(especially southern suburbs) before extending to the Sunshine Coast. Two people drowned in separate incidents but both from cars driving through flooded road ways. Many vehicles and properties experienced flooding/inundation to various depths. Highest rainfall in the 24 hours to 9am Saturday morning was Logan City 284 mm. A number of other registrations topped 200mm. Rainfalls at various locations exceeded the 1 in 100 year figure
Severe storm hit a property 7km out of Calliope. 30cm diameter trees were snapped like matches, 5000 gallon water tank blown away, 600 m of trees flattened.

A heavy thunderstorm occurred at Cairns between 2am and 4am on January 22nd. 213mm was recorded by the pluviograph between 9pm on the 21st and 6am on the 22nd, with 189 falling between 9pm and 3am. A fall of >185mm in 2 hours gives an ARI of greater than 100 years.
Golf ball sized hail reported from Apis Creek homestead, SW of Marlborough.

E-mail report follows: I am located 35km SW of Longreach along the Jundah Road at the Jindalee Over the Horizon Radar. Yesterday at 1830 local we saw a large funnel shaped cloud on the ground approx. 5 to 10 km south of us. Its direction was straight towards us but impossible to estimate speed. After observing for some minutes
column10: it got the wobbles and in about 10 seconds had completely disappeared?""

Thunderstorm winds - described as a "mini-tornado" or "whirley-wind" - tore roofing iron from farm sheds and stripped and twisted trees north of Biggenden. An 800m strip of the Biggenden to Maryborough road was blocked by fallen trees.

50mm recorded in the hour 4-5pm (ARI 10-20 years).
80mm recorded in 30 minutes at approximately 6pm (ARI > 100 years).

56.4mm recorded in 60 minutes between 3:30 and 4:30pm (ARI 20 to 50 years), including 42.6mm in 34 minutes between 3:56 and 4:30pm (ARI 20 to 50 years).

Torrential rain from a thunderstorm between approximately 10 and 11:30am produced flash flooding in Gladstone. 48.2mm was recorded in an hour at the airport, then the AWS failed.

Houses were unroofed in Granville (near Maryborough) and Urangan (near Hervey Bay), fallen trees broke windows at a house in Beaver Rock (east of Maryborough) and flying debris smashed fibro walls at Urangan. This is likely to have been from the same storm system that caused the above two reports at Maryborough and Hervey Bay.

Houses were unroofed in Granville (near Maryborough) and Urangan (near Hervey Bay), fallen trees broke windows at a house in Beaver Rock (east of Maryborough) and flying debris smashed fibro walls at Urangan. This is likely to have been from the same storm system that caused the above two reports at Maryborough and Hervey Bay.

Houses were unroofed in Granville (near Maryborough) and Urangan (near Hervey Bay), fallen trees broke windows at a house in Beaver Rock (east of Maryborough) and flying debris smashed fibro walls at Urangan. This is likely to have been from the same storm system that caused the above two reports at Maryborough and Hervey Bay.
Torrential rain from a thunderstorm produced flash flooding in Maryborough. 103.2mm fell between 6 and 9pm (ARI 10 to 20 years).

Flash flooding reported from Mackay harbour area including a caf innundated and water damage to public facilities. Mackay WSO recorded 99.8mm recorded between 9:53 and 11:01am (ARI 20 to 50 years).
Significant flash flooding in the Gindie area including several crops completely submerged. Other roads in the general area cut. Fences brought down and damage to railway lines in the Gindie area.%D

Stationary storm cells produced huge overnight totals and flooding in the Gindie area. Several crops completely submerged, roads cut. 24 hour falls to 9am 5th January included Arcturus Downs 397mm, 287mm at Gindie, 289mm at Kammel Siding, 347mm at Emembi Downs, 175mm at Springton. 160mm fell at Arcturus downs between 3 and 5am.
Flash flooding in the Mt Morgan/Rockhampton area closed the Burnett Highway and other roads for over 4 hours. Fallen trees reported also.
Supercell produced flash flooding in Mackay and torrential rain on Hamilton Island. Mackay WSO recorded 68mm in 30 minutes (ARI 20 to 50 years).
70mm recorded at Camp Mountain in 45 minutes (ARI 10 to 20 years).
84mm recorded at Belmont in 40 minutes (ARI 50 to 100 years). The bridge at Belmont was submerged by 3-4 inches.
Several homes innundated in a cloudburst at Brassal in which 70mm fell in "a few minutes". Flash flooding also reported from the Old Cleveland Road area.
58mm in 45 minutes recorded by storm spotter at Yengarie (ARI 10 to 20 years).
This event mainly a giant hail event, but flash flooding was also reported from Esk.
77mm in 30 minutes recorded by Lenthall's Dam Alert (ARI > 100 years).
Flash flooding reported from the lower areas of the Toowoomba CBD.
67mm in 30 minutes recorded by Maleny Alert (ARI 50-100 years).

Unofficial record of 80mm in 20 minutes at property on Rosedale Road 5-10km out of Bundaberg. ARI > 100 years if accurate.
3 sheds destroyed. 2 cows killed by flying debris. At another property, haysheds were destroyed and trees and power lines brought down.%D
55mm of rain recorded in 40 minutes (ARI 10-20 years) at Alton Downs, 15km west of Rockhampton.
Sails of a boat shredded in Shoalwater Bay at approx. 7:30pm
50mm recorded in 20 minutes (ARI 50-100 years). Giant hail also occurred.
Flash flooding with storm (severe gusts and hail also reported).

Storm produced flash flooding in Biloela. Floodwater entered shops in the CBD. Teenager sucked through a culvert by floodwater. 76.2mm recorded at Thangool Airport between 9am and noon (ARI 10 to 20 years). 24 hour fall of 119.4mm at Biloela-Valbona rainfall station.
Heavy convective rainfall on the Sunshine Coast. 110mm in 60 minutes at Yandina Alert (ARI > 100 years). Flash flooding in Maroochydore - traffic created "bow waves" which washed into homes.
Large hailstorm damaged mango, avocado, and lychee crops in the Childers area approximately 3-3:20 pm.
Unofficial report of 115mm in 30 minutes from the Rosedale storm in the Rosedale/Baffle Creek area. ARI > 100 years if correct.

Possible tornado affected the Baffle Creek and Rosedale (50km NW Bundaberg, 24.6S 151.9E) areas. In Rosedale, houses were unroofed and trees snapped. A shed was lifted and carried about a kilometre. A garage was totally destroyed. A water tank of unknown origin was dumped next to the dam of a property. Golf ball hail also accompanied the storm, destroying watermelon and passionfruit crops. Radar indicates the storm struck approximately 4:50pm.
Hail the size of cricket balls reported from the Boompa/Lakeside area (SE Biggenden). Trees, gardens and pasture were stripped. Storm struck approximately 5-5:20 pm.
24 hour fall of 250mm+ (gauge overflowed) at Turkey Beach. Radar indicates this fell mostly between midnight and 4am.
24 hour fall of 300mm at Burnett Heads. Radar indicates this mostly fell between 1am and 7am.
Flash flooding in the Peak Downs (Capella) shire. A porsche and a landcruiser abandoned on flooded crossings.
Storm spotter recorded 80mm in 90 minutes from a thunderstorm at Coochiemudlo Island (ARI 10 to 20 years).
108mm recorded in the 2 hours to 3:15pm (ARI 20-50 years). Flash flooding also reported from Kenmore. Unconfirmed report of 90mm in 20 minutes at Moorooka.

Some flash flooding with a car washed off the road at Nerang during the afternoon.

120 km/h wind gust recorded at Brisbane Airport at 4:59 pm.

Trees and power lines were felled throughout southeast Queensland, causing 113,000 homes to be blacked out. Commuter rail services to northern Brisbane suburbs were delayed by 90 minutes due to power outages.

In the Gympie area, damage reports included large sections of roofing removed from houses, as well as damage to outbuildings. Approximately 30 houses received some kind of structural damage. Large trees were snapped off or uprooted.

At Camira, 85 homes were damaged by wind, both through roofs being torn off and trees blown over onto them. A pergola was ripped from one home (also in Camira) and dumped two houses away at about 6:30pm.
