Fast moving  nocturnal tornado, probably non-supercell. 13 Houses damaged, four losing all or part of roof plus other structural damage. 2 cows killed by flying roffing iron. About 2,000 large trees (to 50 metres) felled. Entire stands of smaller trees felled and damaged. Eyewhitness saw glowing blue ball"."
Landspout/waterspout-videotaped
Golff-ball size hail
Large hail
Tornado sighted, No damage reported
Substantial shed and other outbuildings destyroyed.  Many Large healthy trees destroyed. Lump of concrete tossed 50 meters.  Second track also seen nearby, tracks may have split.

Heavy rain, thunder, lightning and hurricane force winds reported. A pavillion at the showgrounds was wrecked. Roofs were lifted off houses, power lines brought down. Was caused by a severe cold front and a deep low SW of Strahan.
TS with 42 knot winds blew trees down. Heavy rain caused flash flooding.
TS saw winds reach 130km/h (>70 kts) for a few minutes. A police transmitter was knocked out and the roof blown off a house.
TS with strong winds. In the 3 hours between 3pm and 6pm 11.2mm fell causing flash floods.

A TS with high winds, marble sized hail and torrential rain hit the coast near Flowerdale. Worst of the damage appeared to be in a swathe 3km wide. It lasted 5 to 10 minutes. Power lines were broken and flung over buildings, trees and power poles were felled, houses and barns were damaged and more than a foot of hail settled. 30mm to 40mm of rain fell in minutes. The storm hit between 7pm and 7.30pm.
TS dropped 25mm of rain in 45 minutes.
TS with wind gusts of up to 97km/h (52.4 kts) and 6mm of rain in half an hour.

Heavy rainfall during a severe electrical storm. The rain caused an estimated $500,000 damage to one furniture shop. There was flash flooding with the heaviest falls of rain after 3pm. Launceston A/p reported a 24 hour total of 20mm.

Storm with hailstones as large as 10 cent pieces. The hail blanketed a large area of the town and surrounds and forced cars off the road. It blocked drains and rain flooded the buildings. The hail accumulated to a depth of 30cm in parts.
20mm fell in 1 and a half hours.
A 10 min hailstorm dropped hailstones that were "bigger than average". Rain also fell.

TS lasted only a few minutes, with heavy rain and lightning. A stormwater drain burst. The wind blew in windows, damaged trees and gardens and uplifted sections of roofing. Lightning struck a pine tree and brought down several of its limbs. Sections of the tree were blown up to 50m away.
TS lasted about 10mins. Hail ranging up to golf ball size.

8mm in 10mins. Flash flooding resulted and subsided within 2 hours. Part of the Kmart roof collapsed. Power supplies were cut as lightning struck the 110,000 volt transmission lines. A construction worker was knocked unconscious when he slipped and fell 8m at the height of the storm. Estimate of storm damage was $500,000.
At around midday, a TS with gale force winds, intense rain, thunder and lightning took place. 20mm of rain fell between 12.15pm and 12.45pm. Another 13mm fell before 3pm.
34mm in the 24 hours to 9am. Flash flooding.
Flash flooding and lightning. 31mm of rain fell in the 6 hrs to 3pm. A lightning strike blew the top off a two-way radio aerial.
27mm fell in less than 3 hours leading up to 3pm. Flash flooding a result of a cloudburst.
According to the Bureau it was a 1 in 50 year event. 18mm fell in 15min during thunder and lightning activity.
Winds up to 100kmh ripped trees from the ground, felled power lines and caused 2 injuries.
15mm fell noon till 2pm on the City causing flash flooding.
High end of F0 tornado. Trees broken, 1 thrown over a chicken fence. Path about 150m long and 10m wide. Path direction southerly. Time noon?
Houses damaged and trees and shrubs were uprooted by wind gusts during TSs.
Storms peak lasted about 1 minute. Gusts caused damage to buildings and trees.
Mini tornado" damaged 1 building (lifted the roof and let it down)
column10: and uprooted trees and broke off branches. Damage was locallised."

column9: House damaged at Devonport
68 knot gust at Bell Bay

Flash flooding in Launceston City streets. Launceston City report 5.6mm in 10 minutes and Launceston Airport reports 7.8mm in 7 minutes. A letter written to the Bureau some months later indicated that a funnel cloud may have been seen near Hummocky Hills on the same afternoon.

114 houses damaged in Summerhill. Twelve houses sustained substantial roof damage or lost their roof entirely, numerous cars were damaged, many trees fell and blocked roads, and power lines were cut. The damage was concentrated in an area approximately one kilometre long by 200 metres wide.
Hail reported as ball sized
1000 trees felled in the Derwent Valley and $20 000 damage done to a grandstand at an oval in New Norfolk
A gust removed a roof from a Hobart Showgrounds building
Campbell Town School and Fire Station were partially flooded and may have been damaged from large hail as well. Cars were forced off the Midland Highway due to reduced visibility in very heavy rain.
House roof(s) removed at Latrobe
House roof removed and travels 500m at Ulverstone
At least 4.2mm of rain fell in this event.

Roaring noise heard. Tiles lifted from a roof in Lovitt St Devonport. 3 other houses sustain roof damage in Victor Street Devonport. A garden shed lifted over a fence in Steele Street Devonport. One panel from the 3mx5m shed was carried more than a street away.
Hail was close to the size of a 50 cent piece. 2cm hail fell at at least two other locations (unknown) in the northeast.

At Lorinna, tree branches snapped, trees uprooted, a hay shed 10m long, 8m wide and 5m high was totally demolished. Rainfall totals (24 hours up to 9am) measured in the vicinity were 23mm and 29mm. Tree damage at Ulverstone (probably from the same line of storms).
Very heavy rain with hail, thunder and lightning. Farms and roads flooded. A train of storms over a 3 hour period running almost east/west across King Island from Currie to Naracoopa.
Gutters and downpipes overflowed and roads were awash. The rain was so heavy, small birds sheltered under a verandah even though it leaked like a sieve
Trees of diameter 50cm were uprooted and marble sized hail fell. Another storm nearby produced a gust of 46 knots at Hobart Airport at 1547 (local time).
The thunderstorm took the roof off a shack and sent it over the top of two properties next door, landing on the road about 60 metres away.
Gust of 50-66 knots at Luncheon Hill from 2236 till 2246 (local) as an organised line of showers crossed. Unsure if there was any lightning. Gusts of 50-75kts at Cape Grim right through this day.
Hail the size of 20c pieces reported on the Snug Tiers. Hail the size of fingernails reported at 1800 at Kettering, probably from the same storm.
Hail the size of 10c pieces reported, falling sometime between 1430 and 1730.
Conditions were not windy at the time.
Observed from Loongana Avenue, Shorewell Park in Burnie. Some distance out to sea but not as far as the horizon.
The heavy rain occurred between 2pm and 3pm and between 4pm and 5pm. There was enough water over the road to 'surf'.

Storms in the afternoon also produced gusts of 47 knots at Bushy Park, 45 knots at Scotts Peak and 57 knots at Maatsuyker Island. Except for Bushy Park, storms were too far away to be captured well on the West Takone radar. Radar data is for the Bushy Park storm.
The gust occurred on a squall line with a thunderstorm present. The same squall line caused damage to the roof of a building at Forest.
The gust occurred on a squall line with a thunderstorm possibly present. The same squall line caused damage to the roof of a building at Forest.
The gust occurred on a squall line with a thunderstorm probably present. The squall line went on towards Devonport and the roof of a house may have been damaged there as well.
The gust occurred with a thunderstorm.
NULL
Rain began at 0420 (local time) and continued for 3 hours.
Ground coverage by hail reported as between 25% and 50%.
Tunnack automatic weather station. 8mm fell in 10 minutes and a further 19mm fell in the next hour.

Rainfall report by and ex-Bureau observer. He observed enough water flowing in gutters to make a parked VW move along the road a little. The SES reported some houses in the northern suburbs (Montrose from memory) were flooded. They reported some small hail too.
Rainfall measured at Wynyard Airport automatic weather station.
Rainfall measured at Grove automatic weather station.
Rainfall measured at Devonport Airport automatic weather station.
Ground coverage by hail reported as up to 50%.
Flash flooding was reported by another storm spotter on King Island with up to 55mm being reported by a member of the public on the north of the island.
A small amount of large hail was reported.
NULL
Trees were uprooted including a tree 10 metres or more high.
NULL
Radar data not much use because of attenuation.
The hail was reported as being half the size of golf balls with one hailstone the same size as a golf ball (ie about 4.2cm diameter).
The local shop/supermarket was flooded.
This rainfall figure is from the Cape Bruny automatic weather station. The Bureau co-operative observer at Cape Bruny Lighthouse measured 23mm of rain in about 20 minutes from 1650 (local time).
Average hail size was 3.5cm with a maximum of 5cm. The hail was soft centred with a hard shell.
Strongest gust on the Cape Bruny automatic weather station was 57 kt

The hail occurred between 1700 and 1715 local time. The diameter of the hail was measured with a ruler. Another report from nearby said the hail was a little bigger than golf ball size, smashing a car windscreen and denting the bodywork.
This rainfall figure is from the Bushy Park automatic weather station. The Bushy Park Roadhouse was flooded.
15-20 fences were washed out on 3 farms around the Kempton area.
NULL
Roads in the northern suburbs of Hobart were awash with many cars stranded in floodwaters. Creeks overflowed. Firefighters attended 53 fire alarms activated after flooding caused electrical faults.
NULL

29mm of rain was recorded in the 24 hours up to 9am on February 17th at Bellerive. In the eastern suburbs of Hobart there was flash flooding with motorists having to pull over until roads cleared. The storm water system overflowed on to the soccer grounds at Wentworth Park where people were seen skimboarding.
42mm of rain fell and gusts occurred, strong enough to bring down some trees (size unknown). This storm had earlier caused flash flooding in Howrah.
Gusts strong enough to bring down some trees (size unknown) were reported, along with hail at least 2cm in diameter.
NULL

Flash flooding was reported at Invermay. 17mm of rain fell at Launceston (Ti Tree Bend) in 60 minutes. A member of the public reported 92mm of rain falling on the Mt. Barrow road within a short time. 61mm of rain fell at Mt. Barrow South in the 24 hours up till 9am on May 4th.
The thunderstorm which caused this gust was on a very organised line of storms.

Damage occurred at Somerset and Burnie. Signs were blown off buildings, a roof was damaged at Somerset and windows broken and a wall was blown down. Tree limbs and trees were also blown down, including some at West Ulverstone and Wilmot.
Flash flooding occurred at Rokeby. Bellerive recorded 19mm of rain in the 24 hours to 9am on 4/12/2007.
There were reports of flooding in Hobart streets. No callouts to the SES.
NULL
The Bureau rain gauge at Moorleah reported 36 millimetres in the 24 hours up to 9am on May 27th. A large amount of small hail fell at Flowerdale, in places up to a metre deep.
On a farming property, an onion paddock was washed away, roads were covered in mud, there was a large amount of small hail.
Flash flooding and roof damage was reported at Wynyard.
Many streets were flooded around Somerset and Burnie, including North Terrace. Some damage to roofs was reported. Small hail to a depth of 150mm was reported about 1km east of Howth.
NULL
Tasmania set a new maximum temperature record of 42.2 degrees at Scamander on this day.

Many residents of Gray experienced damage to houses, gradens and vehicles. A number of large trees came down during the storm. Rainfall at Gray was about 25mm in 30 minutes. 23mm of rain in 13 minutes had earlier fallen at Fingal (storm spotter report) with hail 1.5cm in diameter also reported. There may have been some flash flooding at Fingal. (The Fingal Hotel may have been flooded).

Some people driving through the area after the storm saw 8 to 10 vehicle loads of people in a campground, all with damage to cars and caravans. Panels were dented and windscreens and mirrors were broken. A number of birds had also been killed. Hail size ranged from small to 65 to 70mm in diameter.
A second storm 0850-0930 UTC brought a further 24mm of rain in 40 minutes.
There was some property damage reported with this event, but I am not sure whether it was flash flooding or something else.
There were a number of buildings that sustained roof damage. The front of one brick home was demolished. The damage suggests a tornado was quite possible.
A number of buildings and roofs damaged in the Wynyard, Flowerdale area, and lot of tree damage. The damage suggests at least one tornado was quite possible.
NULL
NULL
Trees damaged with tops taken out and some trees uprooted. Diameter of some trees near 1 metre. Damage occurred where the Brushy Rivulet and the B72 road meet
A band of damage through a farming property. Tops of trees were twisted off, there was some roof damage, the (private)anemometer on the house roof measured a gust of 157km/h.

Many reports of damage between the coast and Scottsdale, mainly trees being damaged or uprooted, broken glass, and sheds damaged or destroyed. A number of damage reports on the Bridport/Scottsdale road. One report of a swathe of trees 200m long and 30m wide lying in a ne/sw direction near Mt. Stronach. See separate tornado entry.
A funnel cloud was sighted heading towards Branxholm. A number of trees smashed down on Billycock Hill nearby.

The gust of 194km/h was measured on the Bureau AWS at Scottsdale. The tornado appeared to pass very close by the AWS. Nearby, an old bus was blown over and a child's swing set was moved about 50 metres.  The tornado passed nearby the house of the Bureau's co-operative observer who saw tree branches and sheets of corrugated iron being blown past the AWS about 30 to 40 metres away. There was extensive tree damage to at least one property near the tornado track.
Many trees knocked over or snapped off between Winnaleah and Gladstone. Uprooted trees had diameters up to 800mm.
A lot of tree damage around Lottah.
NULL

Trees were snapped off and a dinghy blown away at Green Point near Marrawah as a squall line crossed. Tree damage was reported on the Arthur River, with tops of trees broken out and some trunks twisted off. The diameter of the trees and limbs was estimated at 300 to 375mm. The damage path tended to jump some sections of the bush and then resume further on. This could be the damage path of a tornado. Cape Grim maximum gust was 78 knots at 0639 UTC as the squall line hit.
The SES reported structural damage (unspecified)in Smithton as the squall line hit.
The SES reported structural damage (unspecified)in Wynyard, Ridgley, Burnie and Ulverstone as the squall line hit.
The SES reported structural damage (unspecified)in Devonport as the squall line hit.
The SES reported structural damage (unspecified)in Sheffield and Chudleigh as the squall line hit.
NULL

There was flash flooding at Youngtown (an office and the supermarket were flooded), and drifts of small hail (quite deep-one report of 75mm deep) around Launceston. One plane circled Low Head for 45 minutes then diverted to Hobart. 15mm of rain fell in 10 minutes at Launceston Airport. 31mm fell at Evandale, 32 to 35mm fell at perth and 11mm fell at Kings Meadows.

An almost stationary thunderstorm was located near Maria island for many hours and caused extensive flooding and damage around the Darlington area. The AWS at Point Lesueur recorded 37mm in 6 hours, and a(lower than Darlington) 24 hour total of 69mm to 9am on November 29th. Swansea recorded 83mm as a 24 hour total and one house and one car were flooded.
NULL
NULL

There was no known flash flooding but some large 24 hour rainfall totals in the east (eg 87mm at Chain of Lagoons). There were a number of reports of deep falls of small hail (eg 2cm deep at Evandale, and another report of 12cm deep at Evandale, and enough depth of small hail on the Lake Leake road to stop traffic passing).

Retired Bureau co-operative observer at Evandale reported 26mm in 70 minutes. Earlier the storm had been seen rotating at Longford when heavy hail of 1cm diameter fell. A storm spotter near Cressy reported 28mm of rain from the storm and some small hail. Other 24 hour rainfall figures to 9am on 11/2/2010 included 30mm at Cressy House, 19mm at Longford, and two records of 30mm at Perth.
Rainfall at Gray (Blueberry Cottage) was 203mm in the 24 hours to 9am on May 29th.

A train of thunderstorms caused very heavy rain. The report of 158mm of rain in 180 minutes was unconfirmed, but serious flash flooding did occur with residents trapped in their homes and people trapped in a car on a bridge before being rescued. Rainfall amounts in the 25 hours to 9am on May 29th in the area near St Marys ranged from 123mm to 214mm.
Walnut sized hail was reported by a resident of Gepp Parade, Goodwood/Derwent Park

About 4pm a thunderstorm developed over the northern suburbs of Hobart, tracked over the eastern shore and over Hobart Airport causing flash flooding. There was a report from a Rosetta resident of about 100mm of rain, most of which came with the storm. Hobart Airport received 22mm in 25 minutes and 16mm in 10 minutes. Reports in The Mercury indicated that the Brooker Highway was flooded near Derwent Park Road and that Risdon Road was flooded near New Town Creek.  Many houses suffered flooding through doorways and through roofs.
No wind damage.
Wlanut sized hail in Gepp Parade, Derwent Park.
Hail was also reported at Port Sorell. The diameter of this hail was only up to about 1cm but there was enough of it to coat the footpaths and streets in a white coating.

The tornados were observed from Port Sorell, appearing to be located over the water near Hawley beach. Two funnels were observed. Good photos were provided of the funnel clouds. No known damage as the tornados didn't appear to make landfall. The first funnel lasted about 10 minutes and the second one 5 to 10 minutes.

Sydney to Hobart Yacht Race competitors who were on the Derwent River about to finish the race suffered some damage such as torn sails. Some yachts elected to postpone finishing and turn around to run away with the strong winds until they eased.
NULL

Water over Risdon Road between the K Mart and the Brooker Avenue caused its closure. Water covered the roads around Salamanca Place as well. Some buildings in the northern suburbs of Hobart, the city centre, and Sandy Bay had roof damaged caused by hail, and allowed water to inundate buildings. The Mercury newspaper reported water inundating one theatre at the State Cinema complex. Some inundation occurred at Taroona High School.
Hail 2 to 2.5cm in diameter fell about some of the eastern suburbs of Hobart.
Unsure whether this cell caused any flash flooding. A cell earlier in the afternoon did.
NULL
One fatality occurred when a tree fell on a car near Margate. A number of boats broke their moorings at Kettering. Both of these events were probably due to this storm.%D
The Hobart Cup was cancelled. There were power outages to many Aurora customers and damage to the 'sideshow alley' rides set up for the Hobart Regatta.
There was no known damage from this funnel cloud. It may not have been associated with a thunderstorm. No lightning was detected in the area at the time.

The tornado was observed for 5 to 10 minutes. Rotation was evident, there was whirling dust/debris near ground level and a howling noise was heard. The path the tornado took was from the southeast to the northwest. The tornado was about 50m in width and travelled about 1.5km. No damage was observed.
Large amounts of small hail was reported with this storm.

Thunderstorms caused flash flooding and dropped large amounts of small hail around Kingston. The Vodaphone call centre at Kingston was closed with 560 workers returning home as water entered the roof causing an electrical hazard.
Large amounts of small hail was observed by Bureau forecasters who drove through the area.
Thunderstorms caused flash flooding and dropped large amounts of small hail around Rokeby. The Howrah Garden Centre suffered some flooding.
blew out windsock

anemometer u/s winds estimated. FSU wind speed reading low, had shown a gust of 55 kts.
Stronger gusts in town. Gap hotel damaged, broken wall panel, flashing off part of roof, several trees uprooted and branches broken, water damage inside building.

Funnel cloud reported 3 - 4 km north of airport. Estimate the funnel cloud was in the right front quadrant of the Cb. The feature was well developed when first sighted, it was lost to sight due to poor vis after 5 minutes. No signs of damage found in the area.
Hail upto 2 cm at airstrip, smaller at homestead. Ground blanketed. No rain or wind gusts associated with the hail.
Some roof and tree damage, not quantified
Strong gusty NW winds most of the day.
Hanger door damaged.
A few branches broken from trees.
Squall line produced 53 kt gust about 20Z.
Gust sometime between 1730 and 2030 Z
Subsiquent gust of 36 kts from 2nd storm at 0735Z.
evaporatively driven down draught.
Dust storm accompanying thunderstorm reduced vis to zero for about 20 minutes.
Information in and of month summary from Tindal WSO.
Tree damage indicated that stronger gusts occured in the Warrego mine area.

Power failure, no micromac data after gust. The Goldfields Hotel lost part of its roof, which fell on power lines. A Cessna 402 aircraft had its tail skid removed by the tie down rope attached to a mooring. Some trees uprooted near the highschool.
An aircraft is reported to have broken a tie down chain.
Gust reported in the 1500 synoptic observation from Centre Island. McArthur River recorded a 32 kt gust at 1448 CST from 060.
Hail of 1 - 2 cm in size , one large flat elliptical piece was measured at 4 cm.
Data from PAWA pluviograph and stream gauges
Storms to the south of Tindal.
Gusty storms in the western Alice Springs Region, giles reported 44 kt gust at the same time as Yulara, Alice Springs had up to 40 kt gusts.
Some tree damage.

3 funnel clouds observed from the Alice Springs radar site. T1. well defined funnel cloud which raised dust but didn't touch the ground. T2 formed 16 km to the west of T1, and 10 km to the SSW of the observers. Most clearly defined of the three. Touched the ground for 2 or 3 minutes and snaked around"
column10: lasted about 5 minutes. T3 formed slightly to the west of T2
column11: a broad illdefined funnel

column9: Station not manned, micromac recording and metars
Probable under estimating the gusts, tree limbs broken, out door furnature blown about.
Wind gusts estimated 50 - 60 kts.
Golf ball size hail reported from the RAAF jindalee radar receiving site.
1 house unroofed in Stuart Park, several boats damaged in Fanny Bay, trees and power lines down.
Gust measured by a boat morred in Fanny Bay. Airport recorded 23kts at 1935.
Trees blown over, estimated gusts to 45kts in Karama.
Hail reported in Malak and Karama, no size given.
Harbour reported 35kts at 1250Z
Wind gusts estimated up to 50kts with varying directions. Extensive tree damage in the area.
Squall line well ahead of storm complex which passed to the north of Darwin.
Tree damage in northern suburbs.
Doppler radar indicated 40kt gusts associated with the gust front.
Airport recorded 40kt gust at 0700Z.
55kt, 110 1420Z recorded at the Harbour.
33kts  110 1020Z at the Harbour. Report of an estimated 50kt gust from Humpty Doo area, 41kts recorded at Navy Tx.
Dapler radar velocities gave winds at 48 - 56 kts. A shed was unroofed at Humpty Doo.
16mm size hail and 38 8mm of rain. 1 car windscreen cracked.
26kts at the Harbour and 34kts at Gunn Pt.
Ship in Darwin approaches recorded 50kt gust.Darwin Harbour recorded 41kts, Gunn Pt recorded 45kts.
Airport recorded 38kts at 13:58 and the Harbour recorded 39kts at 13:50
74kt gust recorded by an AWS belonging to the Office of the Supervising Scientist. Extensive tree damage, some structural and vehicle damage.
12mm sized hail estimated.
39kts 1030Z recorded at the Harbour and 35kts from 160 at 1030Z at the Airport.
The Airport recorded 45kts at 1240Z
Tree Damage, some structural damage, school children knocked down.Loss of part of Mango crop estimated at $5500.
Power failure following wind gust lasted about 10 min.
Hail size estimated ranged from 50 cent piece to marble size.
Darwin Airport and The Harbour recorded 43kts from 210. Gunn Pt gust at 0329Z.
Estimated 50kts at the Harbour, by Bureau personel. Harbour recorded 38kts, Believed to be under reading.
Fishing vessel sunk, when holed by 4 - 5 metre storm induced wave. The boat was valued at $150,000 with a catch valued at $4000.
Strong to gale force monsoon stream, some tree and slight structural damage.
The Harbour recorded 38kts.
ABC frequency splitter damaged. Telecom underground cable damaged, Fire Brigade Alarm system damaged.
Darwin Airport recorded 38kts. Several thousand dollars damage at Crab Claw Island due to the winds.
Gusts estimated by Bureau staff from inspection of tree damage and eye witness account.
Hail stones measured after being kept in a freezer,
52kts at Koolpinya and 48kts at Charles Pt, Darwin Airport recorded 40kts.
Inspection by Bureau staff.
Ship moored at quarantine buoy recorded 55kt gust, the Airport recorded 43kt gust from 110 degrees at 1440Z.
The Airport recorded 42kts at 0220Z
Two waterspouts over Darwin harbour observed from RFC at 8:35am CST 10/10/95.  Lasted approx. 5 minutes.
Possible severe wind gust based on reports of tree damage.  Contact number for Mrs Worthington: 889011.
Possible severe wind gust at Noonamah based on damage to Noonamah Hotel - section of roof (corrugated iron) blown off.  Also reports of strong localised winds lasting only 10 minutes or so.
Damage to trees - 6 inch branches snapped, trees cropped.  Clay pot plants blown over.  Very localised.
Small Branches blown from trees.
Trees uprooted, car squashed, partially built house demolished.
Very active storm complex
15 mm rain recorded at the Airport between 1000 and 1100 UTC. 10 mm in 8 minutes on the East Side. Second storm dropped 36 mm in town,about 1030UTC, some streets flooded.
Branches blown from trees, some trees uprooted.
Pea sized hail reported from Larapinta, North Side and East Side, appears to have been heaviest in North and West.
30 kt gust at Darwin Airport, no recording in Palmerston
Trees blown over or lost limbs, over a localised area,  no estimate of wind strength given.
Tree struck by lightning, blown apart, debris covered over 20 metre radius.
Sev Storm & Airport Wasnings issued
Gusts estimated by a pilot
Gust of 35 kts at Darwin Airport. Trees uprooted in Darwin and Palmerston, powerlines clashing together and arcing.
2nd of 2 microbursts, 1st recorded 39 kts.
2 gusts recorded 52 (0832) & 56 kts (1008)
Hail fall lasted 5 - 7 minutes, meltedas it hit the ground, clear and jagged.
Trees uprooted and snapped off.
Some tree damage reported

Wind turbine, solar panel setup & generator destroyed; Ford Falcon rolled over several times, moved 10 - 15 metres; water tanks (poly) destroyed & blown a kilometre away, little water in them. Hail damage to windows of house and Toyota Landcruiser, no size given.
2000 gallon steel water tank (empty) tossed 500 m over a fence, trees uprooted. $7000 caravan blown off road, car badly damaged.
No reports of damage received.
Minor tree damage, roads under water during storm.
Toilet block destroyed (one occupant), some large trees blown over. 53 kts gusts estimated at Curtin Springs by an RAF pilot visitor, 50 kts measured at Yulara AWS.
Tree damage swath 200 metres wide 7 km north of weapons range.
several tree damage swaths, Finniss River AWS recorded 43 kt gust at 0530z.
No damage reported.
Isolated tree damage reported in Darwin suburbs.
48 kt gusts recorded at Gunn Pt, Woolner, and Strangways, other gusts from 33 to 46 in the mesonet area. Very gusty storms during the night. Some tree damage in Darwin.
Large African mahogany tree uprooted.
Incredible lightning display
No damage reports.
Slow moving TS complex, 13 mm recorded at airport,falls of 100 to 122 mm were reported from the northern suburbs.
Hail sizes estimated from Thumb nail ti 1.5 cm.
Tree damage in port vicinity, no damage to port instillations
heavy tree damage, rain horizontal for a short period
Sand blasting of aircraft at airport, runway covered with sand, trees blown down. Interuption to power supply, electronic security systems damaged.
50 - 60 mm of rain in 30 minutes produced flash flooding.
Estimated gale force mean winds reported.
Creeks south of Deep Well Station (approx 24.48/134.01) rose to about 1 metre in 15 minutes.
Reports from OIC's Delamere test range and Tindal Met office. Wind estimate based on a similar event recorded by Tindal AWS
mini Cyclone cyclonic winds snapped and uprooted trees up to 15 m high and damaged signes at the Renner Springs pub.
Golf ball sized hail reported from Palm Valley, Hermannsberg and Ellery Gorge. Several cars with $5 - 10,000 damage each. The hail lasted on the ground for over an hour.
Hail up to Golf ball size damaged windows, cars, Demountables, trees and killed birds.
Irregular shaped hail up to 50 mm in length. Hail also reported from Tanami Mines.
Flooding reported in several residences, TC Primary School and Anyinginyi Congress building, water knee deep in main street.

150 - 200 mm depth of pea sized hail accumulated on roof, blocking downpipes, remained on ground in drifts till 2 pm following day. All vegetation stripped of leaves. Worst hail experienced in 20 years at station.
House flooded, ceiling colapsed due to hail blocking down pipes.
Roof and wall damage, a water tank toppled, trees uprooted from sandy soil .
Small trees snapped, large branches broken from trees, large frangipani uprooted and wrecked a fence. No estimate of wind strength given.
Funnel cloud reported, no damage found

Rainfall 100 mm at Bayview Haven, 140 mm for 24 hours to 9 am, unofficial gauge. Larrakeyah 77 mm, Darwin Apt 74 mm, Parap 74 mm to 9 am. Roads and low lying areas  flooded, storm water drains overflowing. Times are approximate.

Trees blown over, powerlines down some roof damage, plastic garden furnature and toys lifted into the air, fly screens sucked out of their frames. Distinct boundary to the damage paths. Reports of noises like a jet engine approaching.
Dingies on beach rolled over and damaged by wind gusts.
Official gauge at police station overflowed at 242mm, school gauge at 305, two un official gauged recorded >400 mm, one recorded 432 mm.

Gary Higgins wrote: Had a very blowy storm, reported 40 knots at 1500 obs, but said gusts after the obs were much stronger.  The winds lifted 40X20 metre hayshed and dropped it upside down some distance away.  Blew a 4m boat on a trailer through a fence. Blew a large branch onto a new car.  Smashed a window in their house.  Lots of branches down and rubbish all over the place.

Narrow swath of damage and sharp edge of damage suggests narrow microburst or weak tornado. The latter would most likely be land spout where low-level vorticity stretched beneath rapidly growing Cu cell.

Report from Pat Alexander: It was very still before roaring winds from southwest, estimated force 11 (60 kt). Swirling clouds, horizontal rain and lightning (no thunder) were reported, no hail. Damage included roofing iron curled back, windows blown out, fence blown down (corrugated iron with steel posts), large trees snapped and uprooted, big branches down and rubbish bins blown about.

Report of winds estimated to 60 knots around 0430Z from ?Steve? on Park and Wildlife field survey at Chambers Pillar, Maryvale Station. He said the wind shook the car, it was difficult to stand and a tent would have been blown away.
Report from Eddy: Wind was half an hour before heavy rain and hail which looked like crushed ice, some jagged fist sized stones, 50-75mm across.
Report from Eddy: Visibility less than 10 m in heavy rain: 5.5 inches total, about 1 inch in one hour in the storm.

Report from Eddy: Two ?willy willies? observed which sucked roofs off four houses. Wind came from the south and was howling similar to cyclones Max and Gretel. Four roofs removed from two old stone buildings and 2 newer houses, landed intact, complete with ceiling fans, wiring and plaster. Ridge capping ripped off power shed, power lines down and 2-3 dozen trees felled.
Report from Judith: Wind blew down telephone lines, knocked down established trees (white barked gums), broke branches and blew the fridge/freezer across a verandah.
Report from Judith: about 1.5 inches of rain in half an hour (36.6 mm total).

NT News article: Naomi Blewitt who runs a chicken farm on Gulnare Rd in Noonamah reported a ?mini-cyclone? which ripped trees over 20 year old from the ground. A really big storm with huge winds ripped through then it calmed down and then came through again. It was like a cyclone coming through but the winds were changing direction all the time. I?ve never seen anything like it. Trres were blown down and knocked over, one fell down and squashed my big aviary but I managed to save the five sugar gliders that were inside it, a smaller one was also knocked over that had motor bikes in it.

From Damage Report: Geriatric Park, near Finniss River (12.81S 130.46E, 20 km from Dundee Lodge): reported a thunderstorm at 1700 CST with wind gusts estimated at 120-140 km/h, and 5-13 mm diameter soft hail. 10 m trees were uprooted and an aluminium shed blown over; some evidence of shearing/twisting damage.
From report: 5-13 mm diameter soft hail.
From Report: 31 mm rain over half an hour.
USS Essex (Darwin Harbour): 55 knots seen on instrument at around 1000Z. Estimated gusts to 100 km/h at Crab Claw Island Resort on Bynoe Harbour, 1800-2000 CST.
Reports indicate that the trees were all pushed over from the south along a 20km track and that the storm cell movement was toward the NW.

An early evening squall line produced wind gusts of 69 kt (128 km/h) at Noonamah AWS and 70 kt (130 km/h) at a yacht in Cullen Bay Marina. Trees were felled and minor damage to roofs was reported around the Noonamah roadhouse. Minor damage to vegetation and buildings also occurred in the Darwin city and wharf area (a man was injured when a partly constructed wall collapsed onto an adjacent building
column10: and roofing iron and awnings were torn off elsewhere in the Darwin city area). A stack of shipping containers was toppled into Darwin Harbour at Perkins Wharf and an empty water tank was blown across the Stuart Highway in Darwin city.

column9: From Report: Trees in the Caravan Park were stripped and Iron Wood trees that had root clusters 5 feet in diameter were ripped out of the ground.  The branches of red river gums were hurled up to 20m away.  The roof of the roadhouse which contained heavy sections and was 5mx5m was thrown 50m away, windows and walls were damaged and 1cm of hail was noted between 1600 and 1615 local time. A swath of damage was present 5-10km to the East of Erldunda.
10-cent piece size hail reported at Pine Gap.
Trees were felled, causing interruptions to power and telephone services; small hail was reported at Karama and Stuart Park.

From report: Strong winds were experienced at Yulara where it was reported that over 90% of the trees in the area were blown over, as well as widespread property damage. 47 kts recorded at Yulara AWS.

From report: At 40 Robinson Road there was a track of damage about 20 metres wide, oriented in a SW-NE direction.  In places, the damage seemed confined to about 4 metres from the ground.  Above that height, large tree branches and tree tops had been ripped off.  In other places the damage seemed to be near ground level, with a low-lying storage container being smashed and its contents being scattered over a 50 metre long swath.

From Report: Power lines were brought down in Darwin city, a brick wall in poor condition was damaged in Nightcliff and there was minor tree damage around the city. 46 knots at 1:00 am at Darwin Airport.
There was a line of tree damage there which was surmised to be from a tornado with the storm and a "big wind which blew a fridge along a verandah".
51mm in 30 mins = 102mm/h (1 in 10 year return period intensity).
62.6mm in 30 mins = 125mm/h (>1 in 10 year return period intensity).

5inch depth of marble-sized hail at Finke Gorge National Park (20km south of Hermannsburg), the Palm Valley natural gas plant glass instruments were shattered and trees stripped of their leaves by golf ball sized hail, and golf ball sized hail stripped trees of foliage near Intjartnama Outstation to the extent that it looked as if a bushfire had passed through"
column10: with piles of "knee-deep" ice remaining on the ground for several days despite temperatures in the thirties."

column9: The storm caused damage to the bores and pumps at Kaporiltja Spring (near Hermannsburg) and resulted in flooding of the Finke River at Hermannsburg.
Wind gust estimated at 100km/h. Max gust at Yulara AWS was 43kts.
Local flooding reported in Yulara.
A funnel cloud was reported near Yulara
From report: Quite a few branches and trees (some fairly large ones) that appear to have been brought down by the storm that passed through the Palmerston area at about 3pm today (Tuesday 10th).
A 50kt gust was recorded from a hand-held anemometer at Humpty Doo. Several reports of damage around darwin.

Between 1:00 and 2:00 am Darwin airport recorded 93.0 mm of rain which is a rainfall rate with a 20 to 50 year return period. From the same event, Noonamah AWS recorded 132.8 mm (over 3 and a half hours). Channel Point AWS received a total of 180.2 mm from this event combined with activity the previous evening. The only report of local flooding was due to a blocked drain in the suburb of Coconut Grove, near the airport.

Lee Point AWS recorded 68.2 mm in 30 minutes and 96.8 mm in 60 minutes (return periods greater than 20 years), with a total of 132 mm for the event. The pluviometer at Karama measured a peak 10-minute average rainfall rate of 146.4 mm/h.

There were widespread heavy falls, with extreme measurements at Noonamah AWS (171.6 mm), Humpty Doo College (178 mm), McMinns Lagoon (194 mm) and Koolpinyah AWS (178.2 mm). A resident of Humpty Doo reported that about 7 inches of rain (around 180 mm) collected in a drum that day. Local flash flooding was experienced in the Humpty Doo area, with Edwins Creek overflowing, and the Elizabeth River rose to cut the outbound lanes of the Stuart Highway about 50 km south of Darwin. Rainfall rates for around an hour at Noonamah and Koolpinyah had return periods of in excess of 10 years.
There was damage to trees and property, with strong squalls felling branches and trees, and subsequent damage to houses and cars.

During the afternoon ?howling winds? associated with a vigorous storm broke off the tops of some trees, the biggest being an Iron Wood 300mm in diameter.  The squall was described as stronger than usual"
column10: with "horizontal" winds predominantly from the SW."

column9: large disc shaped hail up to "20c piece size but averaging 10c piece sized"
From report: 2 trees were snapped off at their base and that some had been uprooted.
Building and tree damage caused by tornado.
Early afternoon wet microburst snapped/uprooted trees and damaged a fence, carport and school building. Woman injured by flying debris.

Damage in a 1/2 - 3/4 km wide swath with debris flung to the northeast.  A complete section of the roof (5x4 metres) was deposited 500 feet away and a large roadsign (6x5 feet) was also thrown 300 feet from the road.  Two caravans were also obliterated.  A 27 foot long caravan was thrown 45 feet away, with no evidence of drag marks.  Another, smaller caravan (16 feet) was apparently thrown 100 feet away.  However yet another caravan went untouched.
Slow-moving thunderstorm combined with overnight rain produced 116 mm in 24 hours, most of which fell in 90 minutes.
Wet microburst damaged outdoor furniture and boats at Crab Claw Island resort. Damage bill was several thousand dollars.
Afternoon microburst produced winds estimated at 120 km/h in a localised area in Alice Springs, uprooting a tree onto two cars.
Monsoonal squall line destroyed a marquee at East Arm Port in Darwin Harbour causing $700,000 damage and produced large waves which disabled a small fishing boat near Gunn Point.
Minor flooding from a multi-cell overnight thunderstorm. 24-hour total of 120 mm, most of which fell in 3 hours.

Long-lived squall lines with flash flooding and severe wind gusts. Kulgera - wind gust of 74 kn (137 km/h). Petrol station unroofed, trees felled and power failures at Kulgera. Umbearra station - shed destroyed by violent winds.
60 mm of rain in 2 hours from a slow-moving evening thunderstorm (24-hour total of 92 mm) produced flash flooding and cut the Stuart Highway.
Overnight thunderstorms produced heavy rain. 24-hour totals: Yirrkala 284 mm, Alcan Mine 207 mm, Gove Airport 196 mm.
Winds estimated to 150km/h
There was no obs from the official observer as the anemometer was destroyed by wind/hail.
Reports were received of a tornado or funnel cloud.
53 knot (98 km/h) gust at Lee Point. 51 knot (94 km/h) gust at Charles Point.
61 knot (113 km/h) gust at Alice Springs airport, with a grounded plane blown 75m across the runway and into a fence. Several trees felled.
Microburst at Acacia Hills snapped many tree trunks, with pea-sized hail reported.
Another squall affected Adelaide River township, destroying sheds, felling power lines and many large trees, stripping mango crops, as well as unroofing a house at Mt Bundy Station.

Large trees uprooted, including a couple of mahoganies about 15 m tall and 3 m diameter. Tops of large trees snapped off. All fallen trees lying west (base) to east (top). Damage swathe 1-2 km wide. An empty poly tank was flipped/rolled for 500 m until it crashed into a pool fence. Iron rooves ripped off old (greater than 20 years of age) sheds.
Hail the size of 20 cent piece at Wooliana (4km north of Mango Farm). Mango trees damaged at Mango Farm.

Large mahogany tree and fig tree uprooted at Tennant Creek primary school. Rooves blown off two houses and a tin roof was torn off a carport and blown 60 metres. There were also reports of minor flooding. Small hail reported.

57 knot (106 km/h) gust at Lee Point. Dozens of trees damaged across Darwin. Wall of a half constructed house knocked down. Power cut to 60,000 homes across Darwin, Palmerston and Katherine after lightning hit the Channel Island power station.
56 knot (104 km/h) gust at Elcho Island and 48 knot (89 km/h) gust at McCluer Island in monsoon squalls.
A squall line caused extensive damage to trees and minor house damage in Katherine South.

Extensive tree damage at Cooinda and in the Katherine region. 1.3cm hail 15km east of Katherine. 55 knot (102 km/h) gust at Central Arnhem Plateau AWS. Tree and roof damage at Pine Creek. Tree damage in the Darwin rural area at Humpty Doo, McMinns Lagoon and Girraween Lagoon from the same long-lived squall line.
Roof blown off verandah at Waterloo Station.
59 knot (109 km/h) gust. A couple of large trees were felled at Gorrie Station, about 100 kilometres northwest of Daly Waters.
A large steel tank (15m high, 13m diameter) under construction at East Arm Wharf partially collapsed due to gusts from a short-lived squall line. 50 knot gust reported at Fort Hill Wharf.
49 knot (91 km/h) gust at Territory Grape Farm (central Alice Springs District) from storm cell embedded in a cloud band.
At the sunrise viewing area (about 20km SE of Kata Tjuta) there was a report of a severe" wind gust
column10: followed by lots of hail (disk shaped
column11: about 5 cent piece size) that ended up a hand-span deep up against the spinafex in some areas. 30-40 tourists taken to hospital with injuries from the hail."

column9: Large trees uprooted, and fences blown away in storm.
A severe storm passed through Ali Curung around 11am, with the possibility of tornado damage. Rooves were blown off buildings, damage to power lines, trees, signs and fences
10c piece size hail reported.
Another severe storm passed through Ali Curung around 11am, with the possibility of tornado damage. Rooves were blown off buildings, damage to power lines, trees, signs and fences.
Healthy eucalypt trees snapped by storm.
Storm from the northeast produced a 68kt gust on the Dines Anemometer. Significant damage to trees near the Aviation museum.

Co-op observer at Timber Creek observed strong winds and violent rain at approximately 2:30 pm CST, lasting for about 20 minutes. Damage included broken tree branches of 6 inch diameter, fallen trees and outdoor furniture blown over.
25.8 mm of rain fell in the 20 minutes.
222.8mm at Mount Felix. Campers washed away by rising flood waters at Katherine Gorge campground.
52kts recorded at Darwin Airport and Lee Point AWS.

Widespread hail reports over the Top End. Pea-sized hail (just less than 1cm) was reported at Palmerston, Marlows Lagoon and Bakewell (suburb of Palmerston). The first known report of hail at Gove Airport and Alcan Mine (pea-sized). Hail was also reported at Timber Creek the same day, along with damaging wind gusts.

Widespread hail reports over the Top End. Pea-sized hail (just less than 1cm) was reported at Palmerston, Marlows Lagoon and Bakewell (suburb of Palmerston). The first known report of hail at Gove Airport and Alcan Mine (pea-sized). Hail was also reported at Timber Creek the same day, along with damaging wind gusts.
Heavy rainfall event at Hooker Creek overnight, with 111.4mm falling in the 9 hours from 09 - 18 UTC. This equates to a 10-20 year ARI.
Squall line in the periphery of a Tropical Low uprooted trees, snapped one tree and brought down branches near the Rural College (16km northwest of Katherine).

Unofficial 24h total 379mm to 9am 26 April in Bureau-type 203mmm rain gauge. 218mm fell to 5pm 25th - heavy rain from 1pm, like a hosepipe" by 2pm; another 148mm to 10.30pm; >100y ARI. Neighbours' unofficial totals 402 and 405mm for same 24h period. Ankle-deep water flowing into house on a small hill. Train effect in convective bands around ex-TC Monica near west coast."
50kt wind gust estimated by Yulara control tower. 39kt gust recorded at nearby AWS.
Severe TS observed on radar near Humpty Doo. Maximum gust recorded was 47kts at Middle Point AWS.

Radar indications of severity - 50dBz echoes to 16km, elevated max 60dBz echoes. Long-lived multicell storm passed over Middle Point, Acacia Hills, Manton Dam. No damage reports, but marble size hail reported at Adelaide River crossing on Arnhem Hwy around 4.30pm.
Radar indications of severity near Middle Point.
Squall line moving from east - STS warnings issued 19:21-21.20CST. 40kts at Darwin Airport. Radar evidence of 27m/s winds in rear inflow jet. Power failures and gusty winds in Palmerston.
Very heavy rainfall associated with a thunderstorm produced an estimated rainfall total of around 120mm in 4 hours - AEP of 10-20 years.

Significant wind-related damage observed at Mt Bundy Station, near Adelaide River, suggestive of severe gusts with storm at about 09UTC. Several reports of 1-2cm hail in Darwin Rural area (eg. Noonamah, Berry Springs).
Report from Crab Claw Island of around 30 minutes of damaging winds in continental squall line - trees snapped 2m above base, trees felled, flashing torn from units, boats rolled and damaged.

52kt gust at East Arm Port, 51kt gust at Fort Hill Wharf, estimated 55 kt gusts in Darwin city, 46kt gust at Charles Point, 43kt gust at Noonamah. Street signs bent, outdoor furniture blown away and apartment verandah fans bent by strong winds in Darwin city; aerial blown off Fort Hill Wharf gate house, a tug broke its moorings and a boarding gantry was lost.
On radar, the squall-line clearly showed severe characteristics, with a rear-inflow jet >50kts persisting for some 30-60 minutes. Max gust recorded was 38kts at Darwin Airport.

Convergence into the monsoon trough. Almost stationary storm(s) that persisted for around 2 hours in the very early hours of Tuesday (27th) morning. 92.8mm in 70 minutes (10-20y ARI) and 139.0mm in 24 hours.

Significant tornado damage to eucalyptus forest and caravans at Mary River Ranger Station, Kakadu National Park. Ranger reported damage path 300m by 2-3km, heard noise of tornado for around 10 minutes. Trees felled and debris left in spiral pattern, two caravans full of heavy equipment totally destroyed, washing machine blown 60m from outbuilding into tree. Wind estimate from Enhanced Fujita Scale based on debranched and debarked hardwood trees: 230-270km/h (EF3).

Significant tornado damage to eucalyptus forest and caravans at Mary River Ranger Station, Kakadu National Park. Ranger reported damage path 300m by 2-3km, heard noise of tornado for around 10 minutes. Trees felled and debris left in spiral pattern, two caravans full of heavy equipment totally destroyed, washing machine blown 60m from outbuilding into tree. Wind estimate from Enhanced Fujita Scale based on debranched and debarked hardwood trees: 230-270km/h (EF3).
Damage trail indicating tornado event, crossing highway near Wildman River.
Damage trail indicating tornado event, crossing highway near Wildman River.

At around 2am, a severe small-scale squall line moved throught the entire warning area from south to north, missing Darwin Airport by around 3nm. The squall line was moving at 30 knots, sometimes 35 knots during periods where bow-echoes formed, and had a persistent rear-inflow jet of 50-60knots, observed as low as 500m near Darwin.

A slow moving thunderstorm produced flash flooding in town, with the main road being under water for some time. Katherine Aviation Museum received 130mm in 24 hours, and Katherine Bridge had 114mm in 24hrs, 58mm of which fell in an hour.
Tennant Creek received over 80mm in a few hours during early afternoon, 56.8mm in 1 hour, which has an ARI of 20 to 50 years.
A storm spotter report measured a 46kt gust on a handheld Kestrel, and reported branches cnapped off trees.
A storm spotter report measured a 44kt gust on a handheld Kestrel, and reported branches snapped off trees.

Report of Golf Ball sized hail (falling almost horizontally) at Kings Creek campground. Wind gusts estimated at 70-80 knots by helicopter pilot. 53mm of rain. Trees stripped of foliage. Tents damaged. A helicopter was blown over while on the pad. Windows broken. Steel walled dongas with half-inch dents in the metal from the hail.

Report of Golf Ball sized hail (falling almost horizontally) at Kings Creek campground. Wind gusts estimated at 70-80 knots by helicopter pilot. 53mm of rain. Trees stripped of foliage. Tents damaged. A helicopter was blown over while on the pad. Windows broken. Steel walled dongas with half-inch dents in the metal from the hail.

A storm moved over Coolibah Station at 0700UTC (4:30pm CST) A roof was ripped off a house, trees were uprooted (African Mahogany) and 6 airconditioners were ripped out of the walls in a storm at around 4:30pm.
Lots of tree damage on Gunn Point Road. Large branches off some trees, large trees down,etc.
Post event damage survey of the Howard Springs area revealed widespread marginal damage, with some isolated severe damage (broken grevilleas, large branches down, etc)
Storm Spotter report of numerous trees damaged (mainly gums), some snapped and some uprooted.

Lines of storms converged over Darwin around midnight on the 12th, and between about 3am and 5am 211mm fell in 2 hours, which has an ARI of over 100 years. In the end 242mm was recorded to 9am on the 13th.

Delamere recorded four 49 kt gusts around 10Z. The observer at Timber Creek reported a violent storm" with hail (estimated to be pea-sized) around midnight. Large limbs were torn off trees in a strip approx. 1 x 2.5 km long
column10: with most limbs aligned W to E (suggesting a microburst)."

column9: Two 60 kt gusts measured at McArthur River Mine at 0857 and 0900Z.

Cox Peninsula recorded 260.2mm in 24hr (an ARI of 20-50 years), but the raingauge overflowed, with an estimated 40-60mm extra missed. Charles Point AWS recorded 226.8mm for 24hr (ARI of 10-20 years), of which 174mm fell in 210 mintues between 3:58am and 7:28am - an ARI of 50-100 years. Dum-In-Mirrie 10 min data shows 308.6mm fell between 8am and 1pm and ARI of >100 years. Several other locations recorded over 150mm for the 24hrs.
120mm in 3 hours at Wagait Beach has 10-20y ARI
A gulf line propagating acros the Top End triggered convection near Batchelor around 3:30am, producing 91.2mm between 3:30am and 4:30am. The ARI for this event was 20-50 years.

Estimated gusts to 60kt at Curtin Springs around 6pm, large trees uprooted, very thick duststorm (couldn't see end of vehicle) before horizontal rain. 10mm rain, but dam filled several km from station.

Dry microburst 'inverted V' sounding at Giles, with moderate CAPE. Possible damaging wind gusts forecast south of Elliott. No warnings. 63kt (117km/h) gust at Yulara at 0848Z, with light shower (5mm) and duststorm (vis to 900m).
Squall line moving from SE.
Squall line moving from SE.
Slow moving line of thunderstorms along NW/SE wind change line. Another storm with gust to 41 kts at 07:14 UTC.
46.3mm rain in 60 minutes with ARI 20-50y.
Upper trough/divergence and dry mid-levels provided favourable environment for severe winds.
5 warnings issued between 15:40 and 17:40 for a 'northeaster' TS moving from Koolpinya, Palmerston to Bynoe Harbour; Doppler winds to 24.8m/s over Darwin Harbour and Cox Peninsula.
Storm spotter report from Noonamah of large branches snapped off ironwood tree, heavy pots knocked over and loose corrugated iron sheets blown around and embedded in ground.
Afternoon pulse and multicell activity in western Alice Springs District.
Afternoon pulse and multicell activity in western Alice Springs District.
NNW/SSE lines of TS between YRBT and Yulara area, fresh northerly flow ahead of amplifying trough over WA.

58 kt gust (108 km/h) reported from East Arm Port (unofficial Davis AWS) around 4.30pm in 'northeaster' thunderstorm that moved WSW from Koolpinya, over Berrimah, Darwin City, Darwin Harbour and Cox Peninsula. Winds estimated like a category 1 cyclone at Winnellie around 4pm. Power failures at Southport and Bynoe Harbour due to lightning strikes. Doppler velocities of around 28m/s (52 kt) measured at around 130m elevation over Darwin Harbour at 4.30 pm, and a microburst signature was evident in the Berrimah area at 4.20 pm, moving over Dinah beach and the Wharf area around 4.30 pm.

4 elderly passengers were blown along the wharf, one slightly injured, a tree fell on power lines at Darwin Waterfront, traffic lights failed and signs were blown down on the Stuart Highway from Berrimah to Darwin City.

Fresh NW airstream ahead of an approaching trough. Very dry low level airmass (negative dew points) and an extremely well mixed layer to 500 hPa at Giles creating a classic "inverted V". Small amount of mid-level instability resulted in high-based convection and a high potential for dry microbursts (if convection could be initiated).

A multicellular system developed near Old Marrakai, moving westward. There were unofficial reports of hail at Humpty Doo and a maelstrom" with visibility 50-60m and damage to a sail cloth reported at Acacia Hills at 5:30pm. CAPPI indicated two pulses of intense elevated echoes
column10: one directly over Acacia Hills
column11: the other over Humpty Doo. Aliassed doppler winds also occurred near these two locations and a healthy rear inflow jet led to book end vorticies on both ends of the storm complex.%D"

Wind gust Yulara at 0648UTC (4:18 pm) associated with Ex-TC "Laurence" passing to the south.
A storm spotter reported sustained 50kt wind gusts at Annaburroo (outside warning area) at 4:30pm.

A storm spotter reported a 90 km/h easterly wind gust at Dundee Downs at about 6pm. Reflectivity shows the squall line bowing as it passes over an area near Lake Bennett and this coincides with a few persistent pixels of aliased doppler
A storm spotter reported at 12:25am strong winds, violent rains, winds estimated at 100 km/h and 35mm rain in 5 min.
A spotter (David Flint - 27 Lambell Tce, 89818835) reported at 12:30am palm trees snapped and wind gusts estimated at over 120 km/h in Larrakeyah (near round-about to Cullen Bay).
50 knot gust at Victoria River Downs at 5:30pm.%D
51 knot gust at Giles at 0620Z.%D
Snapped twigs, broken branches and outdoor furniture blown over and violent rain.%D

61.0 mm fell between 3:34pm and 7:00pm from heavy, slow moving thunderstorms. 60.4 mm between 3:34pm and 6:17pm is a 10-20 year ARI (5-10% AEP) and Alice Springs airport has not recorded more rain in 24 hours since 9 years - need to check this. The Todd River also flowed, although rose less than 1m and below minor flood level.
Dines anemometer reported a wind gust of 68 knots (126 km/h) at 1:05 pm. However no damage in the surrounding area verifies this strength of wind gust.%D

Thunderstorms developed to the W and SW of Alice (NE of Yulara) at 0430Z, then moved ENE towards Alice, maintaining intensity until about 1330Z (between Alice and Jervois). Radar imagery shows a multicelled line near Palm Valley move towards Alice at about 25 kt. Anomalous left movement was first seen in the northern most cell near Hamilton Downs, which then weakened. The northern most part again intensified as it approached Alice Springs, with a bowing segment and anonymously left moving cell passing directly over the northern suburbs of Alice Springs. Reflectivity. 21.0 mm at Anzac Oval was the highest rainfall total (0.6 mm at the airport).
At 11:20Z 52 dBz at about 12300 m gives hail >6 cm by using the hail nomogram.

Flash flooding blocked two lanes of Bagot Road near Mc Millans Road and there was a small power outage in Winnellie (source: ABC News online). NT News. Severity assessment based on occurrence of Flash Flooding.
Highest rainfall total 138.0 mm at Darwin Hospital.

119.6 mm at Marrara, with 80 mm in 30 min which gives an ARI 50 years

Note also 60 kt gust at Northern Endeavour at 1336UTC. Severe storm cells about 30km south of Berry Springs spawned a tornado during early morning hours.

Local reports of wind gusts around 40-45 knots (estimated), fallen trees and damage to powerlines along the Arnhem Highway.1827 lightning strikes observed within 80km of Darwin Airport between 3:30pm and 5:30pm (06-08UTC).
At Giles (Western Australia) Bureau AWS also reported a 49 knot wind gust from thunderstorm.

Tornado reported in NT News. Excellent video footage filmed at about 6:00 pm (CST) by David Chemello, Gagudju Dreaming Tour Guide with one video of 23 seconds and part 2 of the video lasting 50 seconds. Unfortunately, no doppler data available to verify if radar (velocity) signature was consistent as Cooinda is within Tindal radar range.

13 warnings issued for intense cells embedded in circulation of intensifying tropical depression close to Darwin (pre-Carlos) during afternoon and evening. Evidence of wind strength from Doppler Radar.

Trigger was monsoon trough over Top End together with diurnal heating. Upper trough/low present over the Top End, also assisted with active and prolonged storms in the area. Afternoon storm activity over Roper-McArthur and Arnhem Districts were steered towards northern Darwin-Daly (out of radar range). Another smaller line of storms, evident on Darwin radar, moved eastwards along the northwestern Top End coast over Point Stuart merging with the storms over Jabiru around midnight. 49.8mm fell in the hour between 12:30 and 1:30 am, and 44.8mm in the half hour before that! 94.4mm falling in 1hour 30mins gives an ARI of 10-20 years with an AEP of 5-10%.
148 mm in 24 hours (to 9am 04/03/2011) gives an ARI of 10-20 years. A flood Threat Advice was current.

Slow moving thunderstorms dropped 125.1 mm at Palm Valley (ARI 20 years) and 113.2 mm at Hermansburg (ARI 5-10 years), both in the Finke River catchment, in the 24 hours to 9am 9 March 2011. Many roads cut.

Tornado was not observed by anyone. It was inferred using Berrimah Doppler radar in association with observed damage reports from the area by local residents and BoM meteorologists. Observed damage included significant amount of felled banana trees (80% crop damage) with healthy trunks snapped, some 40cm in diameter, while others uprooted. Reports of sounds of a jet engine" from local residents. Similar damage reports at two other locations upstream from Lake Bennett near Manton Dam and Darwin River Dam. Total path length approximately 50km."
'A bit windy', no damage.

0545 a storm spotter at Bakewell (Palmerston) called in estimated 70-80 km/h wind gusts. At this stage a small area of 23-24 m/s Doppler winds existed within the main SQL. 36 kt at Darwin Airport at 0612Z
Large hail and damaging winds possible but no reports.
The Daly River pub was called the following day but no one had observed any damage from the storm.
Squall line that moved through rural area with doppler winds of 26m/s observed near Middle Point at 17Z but did not verify at Darwin airport (36kt gust).

Protruding bowing segment and aliased winds (between 6:40am and 7:00am with a max Doppler velocity of 28.9 m/s.
51 kt gust at 3:41pm due to a dry microburst.
Radar showed aliased winds of up to 31m/s between Pt Stuart and Cape Hotham. 37kt was reported at Pt Stuart. 36kt was reported at Darwin Airport.
82.6 mm fell in 1 hour between 0630Z and 0730Z. This an ARI of between 10 and 20 years.
53kt gust reported in 4 consecutive SPECIs between 0712Z and 0716Z, direction varying from S, E and N.
52kt gust recorded at 0703Z (4:33 pm) at the airport.
Afternoon thunderstorms in the southern VRD produced a 58kt gust from a dry microburst at Rabbit Flat at 4:18pm.

Doppler showed the Rear Inflow Jet strengthen from around 1450Z just east of Old Marakai, then reach peak intensity at 1510Z just south of Middle Point when a large area of alised winds (max=31.2m/s, 60kt) developed (max wind at Middle Pt=28kt at 1502Z). The SQL then progressed over Humpty Doo and Noonamah at about 1530Z (max wind at Noonamah=28kt at 1530Z, 29kt at 1600Z). Doppler winds gradually weakened from then on although max wind at Darwin A/P=35kt at 1600Z. Difficult to know with certainty whether RIJ winds mixed to surface given the time of night and available obs.

The line began bowing at 0850Z (6:20pm) east of Lake Bennett. Aliasing and a strongthening of the RIJ also began from 0850Z. A strong bow and aliasing in the line developed at 0930Z (7:00pm) near Acacia Hills which went on to Noonamah ( 40kt at 0954Z) and Humpty Doo at 0950Z (7:20pm) (Middle Pt reported 38kt at 0953Z) and Darwin (39kt at 1038Z) about 1040Z (8:10pm). The strongest gust was 41kt at Point Stuart at 0928Z.
A roof of a shed at Tennant Creek Airport was ripped off. Photos sighted.
Heavy rain event in the Darwin area producing flash flooding

Storm Spotter report from Edith Farms Katherine, located almost midway between Katherine and Pine Creek just west of the Stuart Hwy reported 93mm over 3 hr either starting or finishing at 8pm. This fits in roughly with a 1 in 10 year ARI comparing other 3 hourly 10 year ARI values of Katherine 89mm and Pine Creek 94mm.
75mm ay Yulara in 24 hours to 9am on 1st March, including 49.2mm in 92min and 41.6mm in 60min which have an ARI of about 20 years
The greatest 3-hr total during this period was 83.2mm between 12:30am and 3:30am, which also gave an ARI 10-20 years and the greatest 1-hr rainfall rate was 37.8mm which gave an ARI 2-5 years.
YPDN reported a max gust of 46kt with aliasing observed on the velocity radar image at 14/2245UTC. Numerous radar images display aliasing between 14/2010Z and 14/2230Z.

YPDN reported a max gust of 46kt with aliasing observed on the velocity radar imager at 14/2245UTC and 15/0844UTC. YPGV also reported a max gust of 41kt from a squall line at 15/0832UTC Gove Radar. Centre and McCluer Islands had gusts up to 42kts on the 16th.
80km/h estimated wind gust by storm spotter. Storm spotter report also of trees fallen on side of Litchfield Rd, Cox Peninsula with branches fallen and car nearly blown off road.
Many other similar cells on radar in the Alice Springs District region on this afternoon.

Report from experienced storm spotter of 3 waterspouts. Photos showing a dark line of low cloud bases were provided with a hint of a spout column in the far distance. Conditions were described as "blowing pretty hard".
Waterspout was reported by a Bureau Observer off Nightcliff in the morning.
A resident south of Humpty Doo reported a 14m tree had been knocked down as well as lots of branch damage around property. Similar reports of tree damage around neighbours properties also.
Bradshaw recorded a 48kt gust around 12UTC from a continental squall line.
Single celled storms became organised into a squall line near Tindal, producing a 51kt gust at 7:12pm. Squall line crossed Tindal on radar at 07:30pm.
Reports on social media (Channel 9 Facebook) and from NT News reporter of damage in Jabiru from TS, including trees down and large shade cloth damaged.
Widespread heavy rainfall in the area between Gunn Point and Dundee Beach which lead to reports of flash flooding at Bagot Rd and Winnellie Rd. Highest 24 hour total 157mm at Botanic Gardens.
Multiple reports of hail heard on roofs in Nightcliff although no visual observations.
Two squall lines moved over the Darwin region with Doppler wind signatures of ~30.5m/s. Highest gust recorded was 47 knots at Darwin Airport.
56kt gust recorded at Yulara airport from pulse thunderstorm.
Heavy rain recorded at Gunn Point. 108.2mm fell between 01:30am and 02:30am, making it a 1 in 50 year event. 21.2mm fell between 01:50am and 02:00am. Total of 165.6mm fell for the 24hr period.

Probably associated with overnight rainfall near Kulgera between 1230 and 1430 UTC evident on radar. No report from Kulgera due to flood impacts.

Flash flooding was reported at Rapid Creek, Coconut Grove and Winnellie. Water damage was reported to some city businesses. Rapid Creek peaked at 2.98m at the minor flood level at 03:40 CST. Bagot road was cut near the overpass.
An outflow of a pulse storm collided with the sea breeze which then developed a new cell. Reports of trees down at Humpty Doo, small hail at Woodroffe and a trampolie was blown into a car.

Storm initiated on the sea breeze front at 0410Z and was enhanced by collision with an outflow boundary to the east. New initiation then propagated over Pinelands along the convergence of multiple boundaries to the south. Flash flooding reported at Pinelands during the afternoon.
76mm in 1 hour between 15Z and 16Z at Tindal airport in slow moving storms. 95mm for the event, and 40-60mm at surrounding locations.
A 48 kt gust was observed at 0934Z and a 49kt gust at 0942Z.
A storm was reported to have small hail 70km southeast of Katherine on the way to Mataranka. Lots of fallen trees reported by a member of the public.

Possible squall line activity resulted in vegetation damage on Gunn Point Road. Large trees snapped and felled over a 2km stretch of road. A number of monsoonal squalls between the 9th and 10th January showed signs of severity on radar. Which particular cell caused damage is not known.

Storm reports from NT News that the Police Station on Mcmillans Road was experiencing flash flooding. The Department of Infrastructure reported flooding on the Stuart Highway near Harvey Norman as well as the intersection at Hidden Valley Road. Cars partly submerged.
Storm activity felled trees along the Stuart Highway near Pinelands.

Convergent bands from Ex-TC Nathan dumped falls in excess of 100mm due to a train effect. Flash flooding was reported in Parap. Highest rainfall(24hrs) was 138mm at Marrara, 129.8 Leanyer, 125.8 Hospital, 109.2 Berrimah, 101.4 Gunn Point, 101 Darwin Airport.
